-core processor|hexa-core]] [[64-bit computing|64-bit]]\n|modem        = Intel PMB9955 (XMM7560{{efn|The chip marked PMB9955 is believed by many sources to be an XMM7560.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Srivatsan Sridhar|title=Apple iPhone XS and iPhone XS Max teardown reveals Intel Gigabit LTE modem, notched battery for XS, Apple power management IC for XS Max|url=https://www.fonearena.com/blog/264132/apple-iphone-xs-teardown-intel-modem-notched-battery.html|website=www.fonearena.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=iPhone XS Max Review \u2013 The New Way of Life - Compare Phones |url=https://www.comparephones.org/2018/10/iphone-xs-max-review.html |website=Compare Phones |access-date=November 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181002141822/https://www.comparephones.org/2018/10/iphone-xs-max-review.html |archive-date=October 2, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Daniel Yang & Stacy Wegner|title=Apple iPhone XS Teardown|url=http://www.techinsights.com/about-techinsights/overview/blog/apple-iphone-xs-teardown/|website=www.techinsights.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Abazovic|first1=Fuad|title=iPhone XS has Intel modem inside|url=https://www.fudzilla.com/news/mobile/47241-iphone-xs-has-intel-modem-inside|language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=iPhone XS and XS Max Teardown|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+XS+and+XS+Max+Teardown/113021|website=iFixit|language=en|date=21 September 2018}}</ref>}})\n|memory       = 3&nbsp;[[Gigabyte|GB]] LPDDR4X<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hardy|first1=Ed|title=Geekbench scores reveal RAM upgrades in new iPhones|url=https://www.cultofmac.com/576127/iphone-xs-max-xr-benchmark-geekbench-ram/|website=Cult of Mac|accessdate=September 18, 2018|date=September 13, 2018}}</ref>\n|storage      = 64 or 128&nbsp;[[Gigabyte|GB]]<br />256&nbsp;GB (Discontinued September 10, 2019)\n|memory_card  = None\n|battery      = {{nowrap|3.81 V}} {{nowrap|11.21 W\u00b7h}} (2942&nbsp;mA\u00b7h) [[Lithium-ion battery|Li-ion]]\n|display      = {{convert|6.08|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Retina Display|Liquid Retina]]: [[LED-backlit LCD|LED-backlit]] [[IPS panel|IPS LCD]], 1792 \u00d7 828 px (326 [[Pixels per inch|ppi]])<br />625&nbsp;cd/m\u00b2 max. brightness (typical), with dual-ion exchange-strengthened glass.\n|rear_camera  = 12 MP (1.4 \u03bcm) (1/2.55\") Sony Exmor IMX333-Inspired, quad-LED flash, \u0192/1.8 aperture, Optical image Stabilization, autofocus, IR filter, Burst mode, 6-element lens, 4K video recording at 30 or 60 FPS or 1080p at 30 or 60 FPS, Slow-motion video (1080p at 120 FPS or 240 FPS), [[Time-lapse photography|Time-lapse]] with stabilization, Panorama (up to 63 megapixels), Portrait Mode, Portrait Lighting (excluding Stage Light), Face detection, Digital image stabilization, Stereo audio recording\n|front_camera =7 MP, f/2.2 aperture, burst mode, exposure control, face detection, auto-HDR, auto image stabilization, Retina flash, 1080p HD video recording\nPortrait Mode, Portrait Lighting, and Animoji\n(Same as iPhone X, XS)\n|sound        = Stereo speakers\n|other        = [[FaceTime]] audio- or video-calling, [[Lightning (connector)|Lightning connector]] for charging, wired headphones, and other accessories (not included)\n| hac          = M3, T4<ref>{{cite web |author=Apple |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=October 8, 2018 |publisher=Apple Support |title=About Hearing Aid Compatibility (HAC) requirements for iPhone - Apple Support |url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT202186}}</ref> \n|website      = {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190909025832/https://www.apple.com/iphone-xr/|title=iPhone XR - Apple|date=September 9, 2019}}\n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\n'''iPhone XR''' (stylized and marketed as '''iPhone X\u0280'''; [[Roman numerals|Roman numeral]] \"X\" pronounced \"ten\")<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/12/16297876/how-to-pronounce-iphone-x|title=It's pronounced 'iPhone Ten'|work=The Verge|access-date=October 10, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171010210618/https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/9/12/16297876/how-to-pronounce-iphone-x|archivedate=October 10, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=You're pronouncing the iPhone X wrong |url=https://www.news.com.au/technology/gadgets/mobile-phones/awkward-iphone-x-mistake-with-people-pronouncing-the-model-wrong/news-story/43dbe90dfb2c83fdb229ede77627abfa |website=News.com.au |accessdate=12 December 2018|date=September 14, 2017 }}</ref> is a [[smartphone]] designed and manufactured by [[Apple Inc.]] It is the [[List of iOS devices|twelfth]] generation of the [[iPhone]]. It was announced by [[Phil Schiller]] on September 12, 2018, at the [[Steve Jobs Theater]] in the [[Apple Park]] campus, alongside the higher-priced [[iPhone XS|iPhone XS and iPhone XS Max.]] Pre-orders began on October 19, 2018, with an official release on October 26, 2018.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-xr/|title=iPhone XR: Everything We Know|work=MacRumors|access-date=September 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe phone has a 6.1-inch \"Liquid Retina\" LCD display, which Apple claims is the \"most advanced LCD in the industry.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Apple iPhone XR Official Site|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-xr/|website=Apple.com |accessdate=14 July 2019}}</ref> It is the least expensive device in Apple's [[List of iOS devices#iPhone|iPhone X line of devices]], with a starting price of $749 in the United States, $1029 in Canada, \u00a3749 in the United Kingdom, \u20ac849 in the Eurozone countries, and \u00a56499  in China. It features the same processor as the XS and XS Max, the [[Apple A12|Apple A12 Bionic]] chip built with a [[7 nanometer]] process, which Apple claims to be the \"smartest and most powerful chip\" ever put into a smartphone.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nIt is available in six colors: [[black]], [[white]], [[blue]], [[yellow]], [[Coral (color)|coral]] (a shade of pink and orange), and [[Product Red|(Product)RED]]. The iPhone XR is available in three storage capacities: 64GB, 128GB, and 256GB. It is the second iPhone to be released in white, [[yellow]] and [[blue]], the first being the [[iPhone 5C]] in 2013.<ref name=\":0\"/> Internationally, the phone supports dual SIMs through a [[Subscriber identity module#Nano-SIM|Nano-SIM]] and an [[eSIM]]. In [[mainland China]], [[Hong Kong]], and [[Macau]], dual [[Nano-SIM]] (in a single tray) is offered instead.<ref name=\"dualsim_china\">{{cite web|title=Learn about Dual SIM with iPhone Xs Max in China, Hong Kong, and Macau|url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT209086|website=Apple Support|accessdate=September 13, 2018|language=en-SG}}</ref><ref name=\"dualsim_china2\">{{cite web|script-title=zh:iPhone - \u673a\u578b\u6bd4\u8f83|url=https://www.apple.com/cn/iphone/compare/|website=Apple|accessdate=September 13, 2018|language=zh-CN}}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone XR received generally positive reviews from critics and users after its release. The XR was Apple's best selling 2018 model. It also became the top-selling smartphone globally in Q3 2019. According to Apple, the XR battery lasts up to one-and-a-half hours longer than its direct predecessor, the [[iPhone 8 Plus]].<ref>{{cite web |title=iPhone XR available for pre-order on Friday, October 19 - Apple |url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2018/10/iphone-xr-available-for-pre-order-on-friday-october-19/ |accessdate=28 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] started assembling the iPhone XR in [[India]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-india-idUSKBN1X01SM|title=Apple starts selling locally assembled iPhone XR in India|date=2019-10-21|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-10-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Design==\n\n=== Hardware ===\nThe XR has a similar design to the [[iPhone X]] and [[iPhone XS]]. However, it has slightly larger bezels, an aluminum frame, and is available in a wide variety of colors. Similar to other X-branded iPhones, all models come with a black front. The XR has an [[IP67]] rating for dust and water resistance, which means it can be immersed in 1-meter deep water for up to 30 minutes.\n\nThe XR has similar hardware to the XS, but with a few features removed to reduce the price. Instead of [[Force Touch|3D Touch]], the XR comes with Haptic Touch where the user long presses until they feel a vibration from the Taptic Engine. The XR also has an LCD display known as \"Liquid Retina\" instead of the OLED screen used on the X, XS, and XS Max. The display on the XR has a resolution of 1792 \u00d7 828 pixels and a pixel density of 326 ppi, compared with 458 ppi on other X-branded iPhones.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/09/14/iphone-xs-vs-iphone-xr-features-tech-specs-pricing/|title=iPhone XS vs. iPhone XR: Design, Tech Specs, and Price Comparison|last=|first=|date=|work=MacRumors|access-date=September 17, 2018|language=en}}</ref> The screen-to-body ratio of the XR is 79.3%, much higher than the 67.5% of the [[iPhone 8 Plus]] but still lower than most other phones in its price category.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/mobile/bezel-less-phone-comparison/|title=Here's our comparison of the most bezel-less designs among smartphones|last=Hill|first=Simon|date=September 18, 2018|work=Digital Trends|access-date=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Unlike most other phones in the X-series, the XR ships with a single camera on the rear on the phone, featuring exactly the same main camera sensor as on the XS and XS Max,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+XR+Teardown/114123|title=iPhone XR Teardown|date=2018-10-26|website=iFixit|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref> utilizing a 1/2.55\" sensor size and 1.4\u03bcm pixel size.<ref name=\":1\"/> Unlike the XS, it does not have optical zoom, because of the single camera.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://forbes.com/sites/gordonkelly/2018/09/19/apple-iphone-xs-vs-iphone-xr-whats-the-difference-upgrade|title=Apple iPhone XS Vs iPhone XR: What's The Difference?|last=Kelly|first=Gordon|work=Forbes|access-date=October 15, 2018|language=en}}</ref> [[DxOMark]] gave the camera on the iPhone XR a rating of 101, giving the title \u201cTop-ranked single-lens phone.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url= https://www.dxomark.com/apple-iphone-xr-camera-review/|title= Apple iPhone XR camera review:Second to Top-ranked single-lens phone, 1st is Google Pixel }}</ref>\n\nDespite the rear single-camera setup, a modified version of Portrait Mode is included. It works unaltered while using the TrueDepth front camera, but with the rear camera it attempts to calculate depth of field using a combination of the focus pixels on the image sensor and AI, resulting in more limitations including lower resolution depth data and subjects not being close enough due to the wide-angle lens being used instead of the missing telephoto lens. Just like the iPhone XS and XS Max, the iPhone XR also offers an adjustable depth of field through software, allowing the user to adjust the background [[bokeh]] effect after taking a photo.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Color !!Name      <!-- hex codes from product selection page -->\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"2E3034\"| ||Black \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F3F3F3\" |  ||White \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"48AEE6\" |  ||Blue\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F9D045\" |  ||Yellow\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"FF6E5A\" |  ||Coral\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"B41325\" |  ||Product Red\n|}\n\n=== Software ===\nThe XR initially shipped with [[iOS 12]] installed out of the box and is compatible with [[iOS 13]], which was released to the public on September 19, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/features/ios-12-review-iphone-update-latest-software-download-apple-features-a8541711.html|title=Apple is releasing its brand new iPhone software. Here's what it's like|work=The Independent|access-date=September 18, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==iPhone model timeline==\n\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[iPhone XS]]\n* [[List of iOS devices]]\n* [[History of iPhone]]\n* [[Comparison of smartphones]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|lcfirst=yes}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.apple.com/iphone-xr/|iPhone XR}} \u2013 official site\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef | before = [[iPhone 8|iPhone 8/Plus]]}}\n{{S-ttl | title = iPhone XR | years = 12th generation}}\n{{S-aft| after = [[iPhone 11]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2018]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2018]]\n", "name_user": "Ghostofakina", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone_XR"}
{"title_page": "Bowers v. Hardwick", "text_new": "{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n |Litigants=Bowers v. Hardwick\n |ArgueDate=March 31\n |ArgueYear=1986\n |DecideDate=June 30\n |DecideYear=1986\n |FullName=Michael J. Bowers, Attorney General of Georgia v. Michael Hardwick, et al.\n |USVol=478\n |USPage=186\n |ParallelCitations=106 S. Ct. 2841; 92 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 140; 1986 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 123; 54 U.S.L.W. 4919\n |Prior=Dismissed, [[U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Georgia|D. Ga.]]; reversed and remanded, 760 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/760/1202/75648/ 1202] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit|11th Cir.]] 1985); rehearing [[en banc]] denied, 765 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/765/1123/413866/ 1123] (11th Cir. 1985); [[certiorari|cert.]] granted, 474 U.S. 943 (1985)\n |Subsequent=Vacated and remanded, 804 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/804/622/435161/ 622] (11th Cir. 1986)\n |Holding=A Georgia law classifying homosexual sex as illegal sodomy was valid because there was no constitutionally protected right to engage in homosexual sex. Eleventh Circuit reversed and remanded.\n |Majority=White\n |JoinMajority=Burger, Powell, Rehnquist, O'Connor\n |Concurrence=Burger\n |Concurrence2=Powell\n |Dissent=Blackmun\n |JoinDissent=Brennan, Marshall, Stevens\n |Dissent2=Stevens\n |JoinDissent2=Brennan, Marshall\n |LawsApplied=[[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. XIV]]; [[Georgia Code|Ga. Code]] \u00a7 16-6-2 (1984)\n |Superseded=\n |Overruled= {{ussc|name=Lawrence v. Texas|volume=539|page=558|pin=|year=2003}}\n}}\n'''''Bowers v. Hardwick''''', 478 U.S. 186 (1986), is a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] decision that upheld, in a 5\u20134 ruling, the constitutionality of a [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] [[sodomy law]] criminalizing [[oral sex|oral]] and [[anal sex]] in private between consenting adults, in this case with respect to homosexual sodomy, though the law did not differentiate between homosexual sodomy and heterosexual sodomy.<ref name=\"decision\">{{ussc|name=Bowers v. Hardwick|478|186|1986}}.</ref> This case was overturned in 2003 in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'', though the Georgia statute had already been struck down in 1998.\n\nThe majority opinion, by Justice [[Byron White]], reasoned that the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] did not confer \u201ca fundamental right to engage in homosexual sodomy\u201d.<ref name=\"decision\"/> A concurring opinion by Chief Justice [[Warren E. Burger]] cited the \u201cancient roots\u201d of prohibitions against homosexual sex, quoting [[William Blackstone]]\u2019s description of homosexual sex as an \u201cinfamous crime against nature\u201d, worse than rape, and \u201ca crime not fit to be named\u201d. Burger concluded: \u201cTo hold that the act of homosexual sodomy is somehow protected as a fundamental right would be to cast aside millennia of moral teaching.\u201d<ref name=\"concurrence\"/> Justice [[Lewis F. Powell]] later said he regretted joining the majority, but thought the case of little importance at the time.\n\nThe senior dissent, by Justice [[Harry Blackmun]], framed the issue as revolving around the right to privacy. Blackmun's dissent accused the Court of an \u201calmost obsessive focus on homosexual activity\" and an \u201coverall refusal to consider the broad principles that have informed our treatment of privacy in specific cases\u201d. In response to invocations of religious taboos against homosexuality, Blackmun wrote: \u201cThat certain, but by no means all, religious groups condemn the behavior at issue gives the State no license to impose their judgments on the entire citizenry. The legitimacy of secular legislation depends, instead, on whether the State can advance some justification for its law beyond its conformity to religious doctrine.\u201d<ref name=\"blackmun-dissent\">''Bowers'', 478 U.S. at 211 (Blackmun, J., dissenting).</ref>\n\nSeventeen years after ''Bowers v. Hardwick'', the Supreme Court directly overruled its decision in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'',<ref name=Lawrence>{{ussc|name=Lawrence v. Texas|volume=539|page=558|pin=|year=2003}}.</ref> and held that anti-sodomy laws are unconstitutional.\n\n==Background==\nIn early July 1982, [[Atlanta Police Department (Georgia)|Atlanta police]] officer Keith Torick issued Michael Hardwick a citation for public drinking after witnessing Hardwick throw a beer bottle into a trash can outside the gay bar where he worked, allegedly observing him violating the city's ordinance that prohibits drinking in public.<ref name=nussbaum>{{cite book|last1=Nussbaum|first1=Martha C.|title=From Disgust to Humanity: Sexual Orientation and Constitutional Law|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195305319|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/fromdisgusttohum00nuss}}</ref> Due to a clerical error on the citation issued by Torick, Hardwick missed his court date and Torick obtained a warrant for Hardwick's arrest. Hardwick then settled the matter by paying a $50 fine at a court office, but Torick showed up at Hardwick's house three weeks later, on August 3, to serve the now-invalid warrant.<ref name=eskridge>{{cite book|last1=Eskridge|first1=William N.|title=Sodomy Laws in America, 1861-2003|date=2008|publisher=Penguin|pages=[https://archive.org/details/dishonorablepass00eskr/page/232 232\u2013234]|isbn=9780670018628|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dishonorablepass00eskr/page/232}}</ref><ref name=\"Murdoch and Price\">{{cite book|last1=Murdoch|first1=Joyce|last2=Price|first2=Deb|title=Courting Justice: Gay Men and Lesbians V. The Supreme Court|date=2002|publisher=Basic Books|pages=277\u2013280|isbn=9780465015146}}</ref> At the time, an unrelated guest of Hardwick was sleeping on the couch in Hardwick's living room; at around 8:30 am, Officer Torick entered the house (the front door may have been ajar) and awoke the guest, then proceeded down a hallway towards Hardwick's bedroom.<ref name=\"nussbaum\"/><ref name=eskridge/> The officer opened the bedroom door, and Torick observed Hardwick and a companion engaged in mutual, consensual oral sex.{{sfn|Murdoch and Price|p=278}}\n\nHardwick was angry at the intrusion and threatened to have Torick fired for entering his home. Torick later stated that he \"would never have made the case if [Hardwick] hadn't had an attitude problem.\"<ref name=eskridge/> Torick then arrested both men for [[sodomy]], a felony under Georgia law that carried a sentence of one to twenty years' imprisonment.<ref>Georgia Code Ann. \u00a7 16-6-2 (1984)</ref> District Attorney Lewis Slaton chose not to prosecute the sodomy charge, considering that the warrant had expired, and his own belief that the sodomy law should not be used to prosecute consensual sexual activity.<ref name=eskridge/>\n\nHardwick then sued [[Mike Bowers|Michael Bowers]], the [[attorney general]] of Georgia, in federal court for a [[declaratory judgment]] that the state's sodomy law was invalid. He charged that as a non-celibate gay man, he was liable to eventually be prosecuted for his activities. The [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) had been searching for a \u201cperfect test case\u201d to challenge anti-sodomy laws, and Hardwick's cause presented the one they were looking for.{{sfn|Murdoch and Price|p=279}} They approached Hardwick, who agreed to be represented by ACLU attorneys.\n\nIn the lower federal courts, Hardwick was represented by attorney Kathleen Wilde. The case was filed in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia]], where it was dismissed, with the Court ruling in favor of Bowers. Hardwick appealed, and the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]] reversed the lower court, finding that the Georgia sodomy statute was indeed an infringement upon Hardwick's Constitutional rights.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Hardwick v. Bowers |vol=760 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=1202 |pinpoint= |court=11th Cir. |date=1985 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/760/1202/75648/ |accessdate=2018-05-11 |quote=}}</ref> The State of Georgia then appealed, and the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] granted [[certiorari]] on November&nbsp;4, 1985, to review the case.\n\nHardwick was represented before the Supreme Court by [[Harvard Law School]] Professor [[Laurence Tribe]]. Michael Hobbs, assistant attorney general, argued the case for the State. The legality of the officer's entry into Hardwick's home was not contested; only the constitutionality of the sodomy statute was challenged.\n\nA heterosexual married couple was initially named in the suit as plaintiffs [[John Doe|John and Mary Doe]], alleging that they wished to engage in sodomy but were prevented from doing so by the Georgia anti-sodomy law.<ref name=\"decision\" /> But they failed to obtain [[Standing (law)|standing]] and were dropped from the suit.<ref name=\"decision\" />\n\n==Opinion of the Court==\nThe Court issued a 5-4 ruling upholding the sodomy laws. Justice [[Byron White]] wrote the majority opinion and was joined by Justices [[William Rehnquist]], [[Sandra Day O'Connor]], [[Warren E. Burger]], and [[Lewis F. Powell]]. Justice [[Harry Blackmun]] wrote a dissent joined by [[William J. Brennan, Jr.]], [[Thurgood Marshall]], and [[John Paul Stevens]]. Stevens also wrote a dissent joined by Brennan and Marshall.\n\n===Majority opinion===\nThe issue in ''Bowers'' involved the right of [[privacy]]. Since 1965's ''[[Griswold v. Connecticut]]'',<ref name=Griswold>{{ussc|name=Griswold v. Connecticut|volume=381|page=479|pin=|year=1965}}.</ref> the Court had held that a right to privacy was implicit in the [[Due Process Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]]. In ''Bowers'', the Court held that this right did not extend to private, consensual sexual conduct, at least insofar as it involved homosexual sex. The majority opinion in ''Bowers'', written by Justice [[Byron White]], framed the legal question as whether the constitution confers \u201ca fundamental right upon homosexuals to engage in sodomy.\u201d The opinion answered this question in the negative, stating that \u201cto claim that a right to engage in such conduct is \u2018deeply rooted in this Nation\u2019s history and tradition\u2019 or \u2018implicit in the concept of ordered liberty\u2019 is, at best, facetious.\u201d\n\nJustice White added a [[slippery slope]] warning about undesirable potential implications for other sex laws: <blockquote>And if respondent's submission is limited to the voluntary sexual conduct between consenting adults, it would be difficult, except by fiat, to limit the claimed right to homosexual conduct [p196] while leaving exposed to prosecution adultery, incest, and other sexual crimes even though they are committed in the home. We are unwilling to start down that road.</blockquote>\n\n===Chief Justice Burger's concurrence===\nThe short concurring opinion by Chief Justice [[Warren E. Burger]] emphasized historical negative attitudes toward homosexual sex, quoting Sir [[William Blackstone]]\u2019s characterization of sodomy as \u201ca crime not fit to be named\u201d.<ref name=\"concurrence\">''Bowers'', 478 U.S. at 197 (Burger, C.J., concurring).</ref> Burger concluded, \u201cTo hold that the act of homosexual sodomy is somehow protected as a fundamental right would be to cast aside millennia of moral teaching.\u201d\n\n===Justice Powell's concurrence===\nIn a concurring opinion, Justice [[Lewis F. Powell, Jr.]] joined the majority opinion in upholding the law against a substantive due process attack. But he voiced doubts about the compatibility of Georgia's law with the [[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Eighth Amendment]], noting that even consensual sodomy could be punished with up to twenty years in prison, the same sentence as aggravated battery or first-degree arson. However, since Hardwick had not been tried or sentenced, the question of the statute's constitutionality under the Eighth Amendment did not come up in the case.\n\nPowell was considered the deciding vote during the case. He had initially voted to strike down the law but changed his mind after conservative clerk [[Michael W. Mosman]] advised him to uphold the ban.<ref>[http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-9252-domestic_partner_decision_revisiting_old_wounds.html Domestic Partner Decision: Revisiting Old Wounds?], ''Willamette Week''</ref><ref>Shilts, p. 523</ref> It has been claimed that Powell's decision to uphold the law was influenced by his belief that he had never known any [[homosexual]]s, even though one of his own law clerks was gay.<ref>[[Edward Lazarus|Lazarus, Edward]]. ''[[Closed Chambers]]: The Rise, Fall, and Future of the Modern Supreme Court,'' p. 386. \u201cAt the ''Bowers'' conference, Powell told his colleagues that he had \u2018never met a homosexual\u2019.\u201d</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Extreme Makeover: The story behind the story of Lawrence v. Texas |author=Dahlia Lithwick |date=12 March 2012 |work=The New Yorker |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/books/2012/03/12/120312crbo_books_lithwick?google_editors_picks=true |accessdate=March 9, 2012}}</ref> But that clerk has said that Powell had met his boyfriend, and that Powell had asked him about the mechanisms of homosexual sex when deciding the case. He felt that Powell had made the remark in order to avoid revealing that one of his clerks was gay at a time when such a revelation could have destroyed that clerk's future legal career. Journalists have since found that Powell hired more gay law clerks than any of the other justices.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exhibit ''A'' for a Major Shift: Justices' Gay Clerks |date=June 10, 2013 |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/09/us/exhibit-a-for-a-major-shift-justices-gay-clerks.html?pagewanted=2&src=recg |accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Dissents===\n\n====Justice Blackmun's dissent====\nA sharply worded dissenting opinion by Justice [[Harry Blackmun]] attacked the majority opinion as having an \"almost obsessive focus on homosexual activity\". Blackmun wrote, \"Only the most willful blindness could obscure the fact that sexual intimacy is 'a sensitive, key relationship of human existence, central to family life, community welfare, and the development of human personality{{'-}}\u201d (ironically quoting from Burger's opinion in ''[[Paris Adult Theatre I v. Slaton]]'', which held that obscene films are not constitutionally protected). The dissent compared the majority opinion to that in ''[[Minersville School District v. Gobitis]]'',<ref>{{ussc|name=Minersville School District v. Gobitis|volume=310|page=586|pin=|year=1940}}.</ref> which was reversed by the Court after only three years.<ref>{{ussc|name=West Virginia State Board of Education v. Barnette|volume=319|page=624|pin=|year=1943}}.</ref>\n\nBlackmun revealed in a 1995 [[oral history]] with [[Harold Hongju Koh|Harold Koh]] that his dissent in ''Bowers v. Hardwick'' was written primarily by Blackmun's [[coming out|openly]] [[gay]] clerk [[Pamela S. Karlan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2009/05/groups-push-for-first-gay-justice-022106|title=Groups push for first gay justice|work=POLITICO|date=2009-05-05|last=Gerstein|first=Josh|access-date=2017-08-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.acslaw.org/acsblog/stanford-law-professor-pam-karlan-concludes-2006-acs-national-convention|title=Stanford Law Professor Pam Karlan Concludes 2006 ACS National Convention {{!}} ACS|access-date=2017-08-24|language=en|date=2006-06-26}}</ref> Blackmun said of the dissent, \"Karlan did a lot of very effective writing, and I owe a lot to her and her ability in getting that dissent out. She felt very strongly about it, and I think is correct in her approach to it. I think the dissent is correct.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://volokh.com/archives/archive_2005_04_17-2005_04_23.shtml#1114025448 |title=The Volokh Conspiracy |publisher=Volokh.com |accessdate=2011-06-01}}</ref>\n\n====Justice Stevens's dissent====\nJustice [[John Paul Stevens]] wrote a separate dissent that focused on the selective enforcement of the law against homosexuals. The Georgia statute could not be applied to married heterosexuals, as consensual sexual activity within the bounds of marriage was protected under ''[[Griswold v. Connecticut]]''.<ref name=Griswold/> Nor could the law be applied to unmarried heterosexuals, as ''[[Eisenstadt v. Baird]]''<ref>{{ussc|name=Eisenstadt v. Baird|volume=405|page=438|pin=|year=1972}}.</ref> had extended ''Griswold'' to unmarried people. Since heterosexuals could never be prosecuted for sodomy, Georgia should have the burden of proving that selective enforcement against homosexuals was constitutional.\n\n====Subsequent findings====\nAccording to Daniel Richman, former law clerk for Justice [[Thurgood Marshall]], Marshall's friendship with [[civil rights]] leader [[Bayard Rustin]] and Rustin's openness about his homosexuality played a significant role in Marshall's decision to join both dissents. Richman also recalled that Marshall thought that the case was a \"no-brainer\", and told Richman, who wrote a bench memo for Marshall on the case, that \"this [case] is controlled by [[Stanley v. Georgia|''Stanley'']]\".{{sfn|Murdoch and Price|p=292}}\n\n==Subsequent events==\n\n===Hardwick===\nMichael Hardwick died in 1991 of complications from [[AIDS]]. According to his lawyer Kathleen Wilde, he died very bitter about the outcome of the case.<ref>{{cite news |title=Unlikely Allies in a Gay Rights Battle in Georgia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/07/us/unlikely-allies-in-a-gay-rights-battle-in-georgia.html |accessdate=8 Dec 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |author=Richard Fausset}}</ref>\n\n===Jurisprudence===\n''Bowers'' was decided at a time when the court's privacy jurisprudence, and in particular the right to abortion recognized in ''[[Roe v. Wade]]''<ref>{{ussc|name=Roe v. Wade|volume=410|page=113|pin=|year=1973}}.</ref> had come under heavy criticism. ''Bowers'' signaled a reluctance by the Court to recognize a general constitutional right to privacy or to extend such a right further than they already had.<ref>{{cite web |last=Franke |first=Katherine |title=Dignifying Rights: A Comment on Jeremy Waldron's 'Dignity, Rights, and Responsibilities' |url=http://www2.law.columbia.edu/faculty_franke/Dignifying%20Rights%20%28Final%20Proof%29.pdf |publisher=Columbia Law School |accessdate=12 June 2013 |page=1188}}</ref>\n\nThe Georgia law upheld in ''Bowers'' criminalized oral sex and anal sex whether engaged in by people of the same sex or different sexes, but White's decision was restricted to homosexual sex. \u201cThe only claim properly before the Court, therefore, is Hardwick\u2019s challenge to the Georgia statute as applied to consensual homosexual sodomy. We express no opinion on the constitutionality of the Georgia statute as applied to other acts of sodomy.\u201d State sodomy laws were seldom enforced against private, consensual conduct in the decades following the decision, though many courts and state governments interpreted it to justify a wide variety of bans and limitations on the lives of [[gay]] people.<ref name=\"keen\">{{cite news |title=Strangers to the Law: Gay People on Trial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/first/k/keen-law.html |accessdate=12 June 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |author=Lisa Keen |author2=Susanne B. Goldberg}}</ref>\n\n''Bowers'' was used to deny suspect class qualification to gays and lesbians, thus restricting the standard of review to rational basis. Although ''Bowers'' was later overruled, decisions based on it, such as ''[[High Tech Gays v. Defense Industrial Security Clearance Office]]'',<ref>{{cite court |litigants=High Tech Gays v. Defense Industrial Security Clearance Office |vol=895 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=563 |pinpoint= |court=9th Cir. |date=1990 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/895/563/46921/ |accessdate=2018-05-11 |quote=}}</ref> are sometimes still cited as precedent in gay rights cases.\n\n===Justice Powell's later comments===\nIn 1990, three years after retiring from the Court, Powell told a group of [[New York University]] law students that he considered his opinion in ''Bowers'' an error. \u201cI do think it was inconsistent in a general way with ''Roe''. When I had the opportunity to reread the opinions a few months later I thought the dissent had the better of the arguments.\"<ref name = shilts>Shilts, p. 542</ref> But Powell believed the case was one of little importance and in 1990 said he hadn't devoted thirty minutes to thinking about it since the ruling.{{sfn|Murdoch and Price}}\n\n===Repeal of state sodomy laws===\nIn the years after ''Bowers'' was decided, several state legislatures repealed their sodomy laws. In addition, a number of state courts invalidated sodomy laws under privacy or other provisions of their state constitutions. The same sodomy law that was upheld in ''Bowers'' was struck down by the Georgia Supreme Court under the Georgia state constitution in the case of ''[[Powell v. Georgia|Powell v. State]]''.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Powell v. State |vol=270 |reporter=Ga. |opinion=327 |pinpoint= |court=Ga. |date=1998 |url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/1338934/powell-v-state/ |accessdate=2018-05-11 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"keen\"/>\n\n====''Lawrence v. Texas''====\nThe remaining 13 state sodomy laws in the U.S. were invalidated, insofar as they applied to private consensual conduct among adults, by the Supreme Court decision in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'',<ref name=Lawrence/> which explicitly overturned ''Bowers''. Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]] wrote the majority opinion in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas|Lawrence]]'', ruling that Texas's state sodomy law was unconstitutional under the Fourteenth Amendment's due process clause (adult consensual sexual intimacy in one's home is a vital interest in liberty and privacy protected by the Due Process Clause). Kennedy wrote: \u201c''Bowers'' was not correct when it was decided, and it is not correct today. It ought not to remain binding precedent. ''Bowers v. Hardwick'' should be and now is overruled.\u201d<ref>''Lawrence'', 539 U.S. at 578.</ref>\n\n===Media portrayal===\n[[Bill Moyers]] discussed the decision at length in an interview with Blackmun on the episode \"Mr. Justice Blackmun\" of the 1987 Constitutional bicentennial documentary miniseries ''In Search of the Constitution''.<ref>[https://billmoyers.com/content/mr-justice-blackmun-supreme-court/ Mr. Justice Blackmun (April 16, 1987)]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 a play based on the life of Michael Hardwick and the judicial proceedings, ''Sodomy Rules: The Bowers v. Hardwick Trial'', was written and performed by Bill Crouch in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carol Polcovar and Festival Participants: Fresh Fruit Festival, June 28, 2009|url=http://www.nytheatre.com/Content/Interview/freshfruit|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130062125/http://www.nytheatre.com/Content/Interview/freshfruit|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 30, 2013|publisher=nytheater.com|accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an updated revision of Sodomy Rules! (The Bowers v. Hardwick Trial) a solo documentary play based on the life of Michael Hardwick, was written and performed by Bill Crouch in New York City at The New Work Series presented by Emerging Artists, October 7th, 2019. <ref>https://www.newworkseries.com/new_works_series/sodomy-rules-the-bowers-v-hardwick-trial/</ref>\n\n===In popular culture===\nThe last name of the satirical character Betty Bowers, played by [[Deven Green]], is taken from this case.<ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Aqeq7e3jolw | title= Mrs. Betty Bowers, America's Best Christian - EP. 74 | publisher=The Atheist Voice | date=3 December 2015 | access-date=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the movie [[The Pelican Brief (film)|The Pelican Brief]], there is a scene of a classroom in [[Tulane University]] in which the instructor and students discuss this case, with [[Julia Roberts]]' character, Darby Shaw, saying that the Court's decision was wrong.\n\n===Hastening LGBTQ rights advocacy===\nThe decision was a watershed moment in LGBTQ rights, leading to renewed organizing, and directly to the formation of advocacy groups such as [[PROMO]].\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Dudgeon v. the United Kingdom]]''\n* [[Judicial review]]\n* ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]''\n* [[List of court cases]]\n* [[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 478]]\n* [[List of United States Supreme Court cases]]\n* [[Lists of United States Supreme Court cases by volume]]\n* [[List of United States Supreme Court cases by the Rehnquist Court]]\n* [[Sex-related court cases]]\n* [[Sodomy laws in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite news | last = Douglas-Brown | first = Laura | title = Bowers v. Hardwick at 15 | newspaper = Southern Voice | date = July 12, 2001 | url = http://sovo.com/ | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100820004907/http://sovo.com/ | archivedate = August 20, 2010 | accessdate = August 16, 2010 | url-status = dead }}\n* {{cite book | last = Murdoch | first = Joyce |author2=Deb Price | year = 2001 | title = Courting Justice: Gay Men and Lesbians v. the Supreme Court | url = https://archive.org/details/courtingjusticeg00murd | url-access = registration | publisher = Basic Books | location = | isbn = 978-0-465-01514-6}}\n* {{cite book | last = Shilts | first = Randy | year = 1993 | title = Conduct Unbecoming: Gays and Lesbians in the U.S. Military | publisher = St. Martin\u2019s Griffin | location = | isbn =978-0-312-34264-7}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Wikisource-inline|Bowers v. Hardwick|''Bowers v. Hardwick''}}\n* {{caselaw source\n | case=''Bowers v. Hardwick'', {{ussc|478|186|1986|el=no}}\n | cornell =https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/478/186\n | courtlistener =https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/111738/bowers-v-hardwick/\n | findlaw = https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/478/186.html\n | googlescholar = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=14901730125647575103\n | justia =https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/478/186/\n | loc =http://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/usrep/usrep478/usrep478186/usrep478186.pdf\n | oyez =https://www.oyez.org/cases/1985/85-140\n }}\n* [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=989955 The Invasion of Sexual Privacy]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130712144108/http://law.onecle.com/georgia/16/16-6-2.html Text of the Georgia Anti-Sodomy Statute at Onecle.com]\n\n{{US14thAmendment|Due Process}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bowers V. Hardwick}}\n[[Category:1986 in LGBT history]]\n[[Category:1986 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:Anal eroticism]]\n[[Category:Cruel and Unusual Punishment Clause case law]]\n[[Category:Discrimination against LGBT people in the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:United States equal protection case law]]\n[[Category:United States LGBT rights case law]]\n[[Category:United States Ninth Amendment case law]]\n[[Category:Oral eroticism]]\n[[Category:Overruled United States Supreme Court decisions]]\n[[Category:Right to privacy under the United States Constitution]]\n[[Category:United States substantive due process case law]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Burger Court]]\n[[Category:United States privacy case law]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox SCOTUS case\n |Litigants=Bowers v. Hardwick\n |ArgueDate=March 31\n |ArgueYear=1986\n |DecideDate=June 30\n |DecideYear=1986\n |FullName=Michael J. Bowers, Attorney General of Georgia v. Michael Hardwick, et al.\n |USVol=478\n |USPage=186\n |ParallelCitations=106 S. Ct. 2841; 92 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 140; 1986 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 123; 54 U.S.L.W. 4919\n |Prior=Dismissed, [[U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Georgia|D. Ga.]]; reversed and remanded, 760 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/760/1202/75648/ 1202] ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit|11th Cir.]] 1985); rehearing [[en banc]] denied, 765 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/765/1123/413866/ 1123] (11th Cir. 1985); [[certiorari|cert.]] granted, 474 U.S. 943 (1985)\n |Subsequent=Vacated and remanded, 804 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/804/622/435161/ 622] (11th Cir. 1986)\n |Holding=A Georgia law classifying homosexual sex as illegal sodomy was valid because there was no constitutionally protected right to engage in homosexual sex. Eleventh Circuit reversed and remanded.\n |Majority=White\n |JoinMajority=Burger, Powell, Rehnquist, O'Connor\n |Concurrence=Burger\n |Concurrence2=Powell\n |Dissent=Blackmun\n |JoinDissent=Brennan, Marshall, Stevens\n |Dissent2=Stevens\n |JoinDissent2=Brennan, Marshall\n |LawsApplied=[[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|U.S. Const. amend. XIV]]; [[Georgia Code|Ga. Code]] \u00a7 16-6-2 (1984)\n |Superseded=\n |Overruled= {{ussc|name=Lawrence v. Texas|volume=539|page=558|pin=|year=2003}}\n}}\n'''''Bowers v. Hardwick''''', 478 U.S. 186 (1986), is a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] decision that upheld, in a 5\u20134 ruling, the constitutionality of a [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] [[sodomy law]] criminalizing [[oral sex|oral]] and [[anal sex]] in private between consenting adults, in this case with respect to homosexual sodomy, though the law did not differentiate between homosexual sodomy and heterosexual sodomy.<ref name=\"decision\">{{ussc|name=Bowers v. Hardwick|478|186|1986}}.</ref> This case was overturned in 2003 in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'', though the Georgia statute had already been struck down in 1998.\n\nThe majority opinion, by Justice [[Byron White]], reasoned that the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]] did not confer \u201ca fundamental right to engage in homosexual sodomy\u201d.<ref name=\"decision\"/> A concurring opinion by Chief Justice [[Warren E. Burger]] cited the \u201cancient roots\u201d of prohibitions against homosexual sex, quoting [[William Blackstone]]\u2019s description of homosexual sex as an \u201cinfamous crime against nature\u201d, worse than rape, and \u201ca crime not fit to be named\u201d. Burger concluded: \u201cTo hold that the act of homosexual sodomy is somehow protected as a fundamental right would be to cast aside millennia of moral teaching.\u201d<ref name=\"concurrence\"/> Justice [[Lewis F. Powell]] later said he regretted joining the majority, but thought the case of little importance at the time.\n\nThe senior dissent, by Justice [[Harry Blackmun]], framed the issue as revolving around the right to privacy. Blackmun's dissent accused the Court of an \u201calmost obsessive focus on homosexual activity\" and an \u201coverall refusal to consider the broad principles that have informed our treatment of privacy in specific cases\u201d. In response to invocations of religious taboos against homosexuality, Blackmun wrote: \u201cThat certain, but by no means all, religious groups condemn the behavior at issue gives the State no license to impose their judgments on the entire citizenry. The legitimacy of secular legislation depends, instead, on whether the State can advance some justification for its law beyond its conformity to religious doctrine.\u201d<ref name=\"blackmun-dissent\">''Bowers'', 478 U.S. at 211 (Blackmun, J., dissenting).</ref>\n\nSeventeen years after ''Bowers v. Hardwick'', the Supreme Court directly overruled its decision in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'',<ref name=Lawrence>{{ussc|name=Lawrence v. Texas|volume=539|page=558|pin=|year=2003}}.</ref> and held that anti-sodomy laws are unconstitutional.\n\n==Background==\nIn early July 1982, [[Atlanta Police Department (Georgia)|Atlanta police]] officer Keith Torick issued Michael Hardwick a citation for public drinking after witnessing Hardwick throw a beer bottle into a trash can outside the gay bar where he worked, allegedly observing him violating the city's ordinance that prohibits drinking in public.<ref name=nussbaum>{{cite book|last1=Nussbaum|first1=Martha C.|title=From Disgust to Humanity: Sexual Orientation and Constitutional Law|date=2010|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195305319|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/fromdisgusttohum00nuss}}</ref> Due to a clerical error on the citation issued by Torick, Hardwick missed his court date and Torick obtained a warrant for Hardwick's arrest. Hardwick then settled the matter by paying a $50 fine at a court office, but Torick showed up at Hardwick's house three weeks later, on August 3, to serve the now-invalid warrant.<ref name=eskridge>{{cite book|last1=Eskridge|first1=William N.|title=Sodomy Laws in America, 1861-2003|date=2008|publisher=Penguin|pages=[https://archive.org/details/dishonorablepass00eskr/page/232 232\u2013234]|isbn=9780670018628|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/dishonorablepass00eskr/page/232}}</ref><ref name=\"Murdoch and Price\">{{cite book|last1=Murdoch|first1=Joyce|last2=Price|first2=Deb|title=Courting Justice: Gay Men and Lesbians V. The Supreme Court|date=2002|publisher=Basic Books|pages=277\u2013280|isbn=9780465015146}}</ref> At the time, an unrelated guest of Hardwick was sleeping on the couch in Hardwick's living room; at around 8:30 am, Officer Torick entered the house (the front door may have been ajar) and awoke the guest, then proceeded down a hallway towards Hardwick's bedroom.<ref name=\"nussbaum\"/><ref name=eskridge/> The officer opened the bedroom door, and Torick observed Hardwick and a companion engaged in mutual, consensual oral sex.{{sfn|Murdoch and Price|p=278}}\n\nHardwick was angry at the intrusion and threatened to have Torick fired for entering his home. Torick later stated that he \"would never have made the case if [Hardwick] hadn't had an attitude problem.\"<ref name=eskridge/> Torick then arrested both men for [[sodomy]], a felony under Georgia law that carried a sentence of one to twenty years' imprisonment.<ref>Georgia Code Ann. \u00a7 16-6-2 (1984)</ref> District Attorney Lewis Slaton chose not to prosecute the sodomy charge, considering that the warrant had expired, and his own belief that the sodomy law should not be used to prosecute consensual sexual activity.<ref name=eskridge/>\n\nHardwick then sued [[Mike Bowers|Michael Bowers]], the [[attorney general]] of Georgia, in federal court for a [[declaratory judgment]] that the state's sodomy law was invalid. He charged that as a non-celibate gay man, he was liable to eventually be prosecuted for his activities. The [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) had been searching for a \u201cperfect test case\u201d to challenge anti-sodomy laws, and Hardwick's cause presented the one they were looking for.{{sfn|Murdoch and Price|p=279}} They approached Hardwick, who agreed to be represented by ACLU attorneys.\n\nIn the lower federal courts, Hardwick was represented by attorney Kathleen Wilde. The case was filed in the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia]], where it was dismissed, with the Court ruling in favor of Bowers. Hardwick appealed, and the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit]] reversed the lower court, finding that the Georgia sodomy statute was indeed an infringement upon Hardwick's Constitutional rights.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Hardwick v. Bowers |vol=760 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=1202 |pinpoint= |court=11th Cir. |date=1985 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/760/1202/75648/ |accessdate=2018-05-11 |quote=}}</ref> The State of Georgia then appealed, and the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] granted [[certiorari]] on November&nbsp;4, 1985, to review the case.\n\nHardwick was represented before the Supreme Court by [[Harvard Law School]] Professor [[Laurence Tribe]]. Michael Hobbs, assistant attorney general, argued the case for the State. The legality of the officer's entry into Hardwick's home was not contested; only the constitutionality of the sodomy statute was challenged.\n\nA heterosexual married couple was initially named in the suit as plaintiffs [[John Doe|John and Mary Doe]], alleging that they wished to engage in sodomy but were prevented from doing so by the Georgia anti-sodomy law.<ref name=\"decision\" /> But they failed to obtain [[Standing (law)|standing]] and were dropped from the suit.<ref name=\"decision\" />\n\n==Opinion of the Court==\nThe Court issued a 5-4 ruling upholding the sodomy laws. Justice [[Byron White]] wrote the majority opinion and was joined by Justices [[William Rehnquist]], [[Sandra Day O'Connor]], [[Warren E. Burger]], and [[Lewis F. Powell]]. Justice [[Harry Blackmun]] wrote a dissent joined by [[William J. Brennan, Jr.]], [[Thurgood Marshall]], and [[John Paul Stevens]]. Stevens also wrote a dissent joined by Brennan and Marshall.\n\n===Majority opinion===\nThe issue in ''Bowers'' involved the right of [[privacy]]. Since 1965's ''[[Griswold v. Connecticut]]'',<ref name=Griswold>{{ussc|name=Griswold v. Connecticut|volume=381|page=479|pin=|year=1965}}.</ref> the Court had held that a right to privacy was implicit in the [[Due Process Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]]. In ''Bowers'', the Court held that this right did not extend to private, consensual sexual conduct, at least insofar as it involved homosexual sex. The majority opinion in ''Bowers'', written by Justice [[Byron White]], framed the legal question as whether the constitution confers \u201ca fundamental right upon homosexuals to engage in sodomy.\u201d The opinion answered this question in the negative, stating that \u201cto claim that a right to engage in such conduct is \u2018deeply rooted in this Nation\u2019s history and tradition\u2019 or \u2018implicit in the concept of ordered liberty\u2019 is, at best, facetious.\u201d\n\nJustice White added a [[slippery slope]] warning about undesirable potential implications for other sex laws: <blockquote>And if respondent's submission is limited to the voluntary sexual conduct between consenting adults, it would be difficult, except by fiat, to limit the claimed right to homosexual conduct [p196] while leaving exposed to prosecution adultery, incest, and other sexual crimes even though they are committed in the home. We are unwilling to start down that road.</blockquote>\n\n===Chief Justice Burger's concurrence===\nThe short concurring opinion by Chief Justice [[Warren E. Burger]] emphasized historical negative attitudes toward homosexual sex, quoting Sir [[William Blackstone]]\u2019s characterization of sodomy as \u201ca crime not fit to be named\u201d.<ref name=\"concurrence\">''Bowers'', 478 U.S. at 197 (Burger, C.J., concurring).</ref> Burger concluded, \u201cTo hold that the act of homosexual sodomy is somehow protected as a fundamental right would be to cast aside millennia of moral teaching.\u201d\n\n===Justice Powell's concurrence===\nIn a concurring opinion, Justice [[Lewis F. Powell, Jr.]] joined the majority opinion in upholding the law against a substantive due process attack. But he voiced doubts about the compatibility of Georgia's law with the [[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Eighth Amendment]], noting that even consensual sodomy could be punished with up to twenty years in prison, the same sentence as aggravated battery or first-degree arson. However, since Hardwick had not been tried or sentenced, the question of the statute's constitutionality under the Eighth Amendment did not come up in the case.\n\nPowell was considered the deciding vote during the case. He had initially voted to strike down the law but changed his mind after conservative clerk [[Michael W. Mosman]] advised him to uphold the ban.<ref>[http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-9252-domestic_partner_decision_revisiting_old_wounds.html Domestic Partner Decision: Revisiting Old Wounds?], ''Willamette Week''</ref><ref>Shilts, p. 523</ref> It has been claimed that Powell's decision to uphold the law was influenced by his belief that he had never known any [[homosexual]]s, even though one of his own law clerks was gay.<ref>[[Edward Lazarus|Lazarus, Edward]]. ''[[Closed Chambers]]: The Rise, Fall, and Future of the Modern Supreme Court,'' p. 386. \u201cAt the ''Bowers'' conference, Powell told his colleagues that he had \u2018never met a homosexual\u2019.\u201d</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Extreme Makeover: The story behind the story of Lawrence v. Texas |author=Dahlia Lithwick |date=12 March 2012 |work=The New Yorker |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/books/2012/03/12/120312crbo_books_lithwick?google_editors_picks=true |accessdate=March 9, 2012}}</ref> But that clerk has said that Powell had met his boyfriend, and that Powell had asked him about the mechanisms of homosexual sex when deciding the case. He felt that Powell had made the remark in order to avoid revealing that one of his clerks was gay at a time when such a revelation could have destroyed that clerk's future legal career. Journalists have since found that Powell hired more gay law clerks than any of the other justices.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exhibit ''A'' for a Major Shift: Justices' Gay Clerks |date=June 10, 2013 |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/09/us/exhibit-a-for-a-major-shift-justices-gay-clerks.html?pagewanted=2&src=recg |accessdate=10 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Dissents===\n\n====Justice Blackmun's dissent====\nA sharply worded dissenting opinion by Justice [[Harry Blackmun]] attacked the majority opinion as having an \"almost obsessive focus on homosexual activity\". Blackmun wrote, \"Only the most willful blindness could obscure the fact that sexual intimacy is 'a sensitive, key relationship of human existence, central to family life, community welfare, and the development of human personality{{'-}}\u201d (ironically quoting from Burger's opinion in ''[[Paris Adult Theatre I v. Slaton]]'', which held that obscene films are not constitutionally protected). The dissent compared the majority opinion to that in ''[[Minersville School District v. Gobitis]]'',<ref>{{ussc|name=Minersville School District v. Gobitis|volume=310|page=586|pin=|year=1940}}.</ref> which was reversed by the Court after only three years.<ref>{{ussc|name=West Virginia State Board of Education v. Barnette|volume=319|page=624|pin=|year=1943}}.</ref>\n\nBlackmun revealed in a 1995 [[oral history]] with [[Harold Hongju Koh|Harold Koh]] that his dissent in ''Bowers v. Hardwick'' was written primarily by Blackmun's [[coming out|openly]] [[gay]] clerk [[Pamela S. Karlan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2009/05/groups-push-for-first-gay-justice-022106|title=Groups push for first gay justice|work=POLITICO|date=2009-05-05|last=Gerstein|first=Josh|access-date=2017-08-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.acslaw.org/acsblog/stanford-law-professor-pam-karlan-concludes-2006-acs-national-convention|title=Stanford Law Professor Pam Karlan Concludes 2006 ACS National Convention {{!}} ACS|access-date=2017-08-24|language=en|date=2006-06-26}}</ref> Blackmun said of the dissent, \"Karlan did a lot of very effective writing, and I owe a lot to her and her ability in getting that dissent out. She felt very strongly about it, and I think is correct in her approach to it. I think the dissent is correct.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://volokh.com/archives/archive_2005_04_17-2005_04_23.shtml#1114025448 |title=The Volokh Conspiracy |publisher=Volokh.com |accessdate=2011-06-01}}</ref>\n\n====Justice Stevens's dissent====\nJustice [[John Paul Stevens]] wrote a separate dissent that focused on the selective enforcement of the law against homosexuals. The Georgia statute could not be applied to married heterosexuals, as consensual sexual activity within the bounds of marriage was protected under ''[[Griswold v. Connecticut]]''.<ref name=Griswold/> Nor could the law be applied to unmarried heterosexuals, as ''[[Eisenstadt v. Baird]]''<ref>{{ussc|name=Eisenstadt v. Baird|volume=405|page=438|pin=|year=1972}}.</ref> had extended ''Griswold'' to unmarried people. Since heterosexuals could never be prosecuted for sodomy, Georgia should have the burden of proving that selective enforcement against homosexuals was constitutional.\n\n====Subsequent findings====\nAccording to Daniel Richman, former law clerk for Justice [[Thurgood Marshall]], Marshall's friendship with [[civil rights]] leader [[Bayard Rustin]] and Rustin's openness about his homosexuality played a significant role in Marshall's decision to join both dissents. Richman also recalled that Marshall thought that the case was a \"no-brainer\", and told Richman, who wrote a bench memo for Marshall on the case, that \"this [case] is controlled by [[Stanley v. Georgia|''Stanley'']]\".{{sfn|Murdoch and Price|p=292}}\n\n==Subsequent events==\n\n===Hardwick===\nMichael Hardwick died in 1991 of complications from [[AIDS]]. According to his lawyer Kathleen Wilde, he died very bitter about the outcome of the case.<ref>{{cite news |title=Unlikely Allies in a Gay Rights Battle in Georgia |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/07/us/unlikely-allies-in-a-gay-rights-battle-in-georgia.html |accessdate=8 Dec 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |author=Richard Fausset}}</ref>\n\n===Jurisprudence===\n''Bowers'' was decided at a time when the court's privacy jurisprudence, and in particular the right to abortion recognized in ''[[Roe v. Wade]]''<ref>{{ussc|name=Roe v. Wade|volume=410|page=113|pin=|year=1973}}.</ref> had come under heavy criticism. ''Bowers'' signaled a reluctance by the Court to recognize a general constitutional right to privacy or to extend such a right further than they already had.<ref>{{cite web |last=Franke |first=Katherine |title=Dignifying Rights: A Comment on Jeremy Waldron's 'Dignity, Rights, and Responsibilities' |url=http://www2.law.columbia.edu/faculty_franke/Dignifying%20Rights%20%28Final%20Proof%29.pdf |publisher=Columbia Law School |accessdate=12 June 2013 |page=1188}}</ref>\n\nThe Georgia law upheld in ''Bowers'' criminalized oral sex and anal sex whether engaged in by people of the same sex or different sexes, but White's decision was restricted to homosexual sex. \u201cThe only claim properly before the Court, therefore, is Hardwick\u2019s challenge to the Georgia statute as applied to consensual homosexual sodomy. We express no opinion on the constitutionality of the Georgia statute as applied to other acts of sodomy.\u201d State sodomy laws were seldom enforced against private, consensual conduct in the decades following the decision, though many courts and state governments interpreted it to justify a wide variety of bans and limitations on the lives of [[gay]] people.<ref name=\"keen\">{{cite news |title=Strangers to the Law: Gay People on Trial |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/first/k/keen-law.html |accessdate=12 June 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |author=Lisa Keen |author2=Susanne B. Goldberg}}</ref>\n\n''Bowers'' was used to deny suspect class qualification to gays and lesbians, thus restricting the standard of review to rational basis. Although ''Bowers'' was later overruled, decisions based on it, such as ''[[High Tech Gays v. Defense Industrial Security Clearance Office]]'',<ref>{{cite court |litigants=High Tech Gays v. Defense Industrial Security Clearance Office |vol=895 |reporter=F.2d |opinion=563 |pinpoint= |court=9th Cir. |date=1990 |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/895/563/46921/ |accessdate=2018-05-11 |quote=}}</ref> are sometimes still cited as precedent in gay rights cases.\n\n===Justice Powell's later comments===\nIn 1990, three years after retiring from the Court, Powell told a group of [[New York University]] law students that he considered his opinion in ''Bowers'' an error. \u201cI do think it was inconsistent in a general way with ''Roe''. When I had the opportunity to reread the opinions a few months later I thought the dissent had the better of the arguments.\"<ref name = shilts>Shilts, p. 542</ref> But Powell believed the case was one of little importance and in 1990 said he hadn't devoted thirty minutes to thinking about it since the ruling.{{sfn|Murdoch and Price}}\n\n===Repeal of state sodomy laws===\nIn the years after ''Bowers'' was decided, several state legislatures repealed their sodomy laws. In addition, a number of state courts invalidated sodomy laws under privacy or other provisions of their state constitutions. The same sodomy law that was upheld in ''Bowers'' was struck down by the Georgia Supreme Court under the Georgia state constitution in the case of ''[[Powell v. Georgia|Powell v. State]]''.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Powell v. State |vol=270 |reporter=Ga. |opinion=327 |pinpoint= |court=Ga. |date=1998 |url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/1338934/powell-v-state/ |accessdate=2018-05-11 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"keen\"/>\n\n====''Lawrence v. Texas''====\nThe remaining 13 state sodomy laws in the U.S. were invalidated, insofar as they applied to private consensual conduct among adults, by the Supreme Court decision in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas]]'',<ref name=Lawrence/> which explicitly overturned ''Bowers''. Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]] wrote the majority opinion in ''[[Lawrence v. Texas|Lawrence]]'', ruling that Texas's state sodomy law was unconstitutional under the Fourteenth Amendment's due process clause (adult consensual sexual intimacy in one's home is a vital interest in liberty and privacy protected by the Due Process Clause). Kennedy wrote: \u201c''Bowers'' was not correct when it was decided, and it is not correct today. It ought not to remain binding precedent. ''Bowers v. Hardwick'' should be and now is overruled.\u201d<ref>''Lawrence'', 539 U.S. at 578.</ref>\n\n===Media portrayal===\n[[Bill Moyers]] discussed the decision at length in an interview with Blackmun on the episode \"Mr. Justice Blackmun\" of the 1987 Constitutional bicentennial documentary miniseries ''In Search of the Constitution''.<ref>[https://billmoyers.com/content/mr-justice-blackmun-supreme-court/ Mr. Justice Blackmun (April 16, 1987)]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 a play based on the life of Michael Hardwick and the judicial proceedings, ''Sodomy Rules: The Bowers v. Hardwick Trial'', was written and performed by Bill Crouch in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carol Polcovar and Festival Participants: Fresh Fruit Festival, June 28, 2009|url=http://www.nytheatre.com/Content/Interview/freshfruit|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130130062125/http://www.nytheatre.com/Content/Interview/freshfruit|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 30, 2013|publisher=nytheater.com|accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, an updated revision of Sodomy Rules! (The Bowers v. Hardwick Trial) a solo documentary play based on the life of Michael Hardwick, was written and performed by Bill Crouch in New York City at The New Work Series presented by Emerging Artists, October 7th, 2019. https://www.newworkseries.com/new_works_series/sodomy-rules-the-bowers-v-hardwick-trial/\n\n===In popular culture===\nThe last name of the satirical character Betty Bowers, played by [[Deven Green]], is taken from this case.<ref>{{cite podcast\n| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Aqeq7e3jolw | title= Mrs. Betty Bowers, America's Best Christian - EP. 74 | publisher=The Atheist Voice | date=3 December 2015 | access-date=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the movie [[The Pelican Brief (film)|The Pelican Brief]], there is a scene of a classroom in [[Tulane University]] in which the instructor and students discuss this case, with [[Julia Roberts]]' character, Darby Shaw, saying that the Court's decision was wrong.\n\n===Hastening LGBTQ rights advocacy===\nThe decision was a watershed moment in LGBTQ rights, leading to renewed organizing, and directly to the formation of advocacy groups such as [[PROMO]].\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Dudgeon v. the United Kingdom]]''\n* [[Judicial review]]\n* ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]''\n* [[List of court cases]]\n* [[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 478]]\n* [[List of United States Supreme Court cases]]\n* [[Lists of United States Supreme Court cases by volume]]\n* [[List of United States Supreme Court cases by the Rehnquist Court]]\n* [[Sex-related court cases]]\n* [[Sodomy laws in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite news | last = Douglas-Brown | first = Laura | title = Bowers v. Hardwick at 15 | newspaper = Southern Voice | date = July 12, 2001 | url = http://sovo.com/ | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100820004907/http://sovo.com/ | archivedate = August 20, 2010 | accessdate = August 16, 2010 | url-status = dead }}\n* {{cite book | last = Murdoch | first = Joyce |author2=Deb Price | year = 2001 | title = Courting Justice: Gay Men and Lesbians v. the Supreme Court | url = https://archive.org/details/courtingjusticeg00murd | url-access = registration | publisher = Basic Books | location = | isbn = 978-0-465-01514-6}}\n* {{cite book | last = Shilts | first = Randy | year = 1993 | title = Conduct Unbecoming: Gays and Lesbians in the U.S. Military | publisher = St. Martin\u2019s Griffin | location = | isbn =978-0-312-34264-7}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Wikisource-inline|Bowers v. Hardwick|''Bowers v. Hardwick''}}\n* {{caselaw source\n | case=''Bowers v. Hardwick'', {{ussc|478|186|1986|el=no}}\n | cornell =https://www.law.cornell.edu/supremecourt/text/478/186\n | courtlistener =https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/111738/bowers-v-hardwick/\n | findlaw = https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/478/186.html\n | googlescholar = https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=14901730125647575103\n | justia =https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/478/186/\n | loc =http://cdn.loc.gov/service/ll/usrep/usrep478/usrep478186/usrep478186.pdf\n | oyez =https://www.oyez.org/cases/1985/85-140\n }}\n* [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=989955 The Invasion of Sexual Privacy]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130712144108/http://law.onecle.com/georgia/16/16-6-2.html Text of the Georgia Anti-Sodomy Statute at Onecle.com]\n\n{{US14thAmendment|Due Process}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bowers V. Hardwick}}\n[[Category:1986 in LGBT history]]\n[[Category:1986 in United States case law]]\n[[Category:Anal eroticism]]\n[[Category:Cruel and Unusual Punishment Clause case law]]\n[[Category:Discrimination against LGBT people in the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:United States equal protection case law]]\n[[Category:United States LGBT rights case law]]\n[[Category:United States Ninth Amendment case law]]\n[[Category:Oral eroticism]]\n[[Category:Overruled United States Supreme Court decisions]]\n[[Category:Right to privacy under the United States Constitution]]\n[[Category:United States substantive due process case law]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases]]\n[[Category:United States Supreme Court cases of the Burger Court]]\n[[Category:United States privacy case law]]\n", "name_user": "Wx413nseu8", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMedia portrayal", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bowers_v._Hardwick"}
{"title_page": "Rob Gronkowski", "text_new": "{{pp-semi|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Use American English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name        = Rob Gronkowski\n| image       = 190326-D-SW162-1977 (46564316465).jpg\n| image_size  = 240px\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Gronkowski at an event for the [[United Service Organizations]] in March 2019\n| current_team = Tampa Bay Buccaneers\n| number      = 87\n| position    = [[Tight end]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1989|5|14|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Amherst, New York]]\n| height_ft   = 6\n| height_in   = 6\n| weight_lbs  = 268\n| high_school = [[Woodland Hills Junior / Senior High School|Woodland Hills]]<br />([[Pittsburgh]], Pennsylvania)\n| college     = [[Arizona Wildcats football|Arizona]]\n| draftyear   = 2010\n| draftround  = \n| draftpick   = 42\n| pastteams   = \n\n| status = Active\n| highlights  = \n*\n| statleague=NFL\n| statlabel1 = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n| statvalue1 = 521\n| statlabel2 = [[Receiving yards]]\n| statvalue2 = 7,861\n| statlabel3 = [[Touchdown|Total touchdowns]]\n| statvalue3 = 79\n| nfl = GRO135948\n| pfr = GronRo00\n|statlabel4=Passes defensed|statvalue4=1}}\n'''Robert James Gronkowski'''<ref>{{cite podcast|title=Pardon My Take |publisher= [[iHeartRadio]]|date=2 March 2020|time=50:42|url=https://www.iheart.com/podcast/58-pardon-my-take-28312029/episode/rob-gronkowski-this-is-march-james-58524227/ |quote=\"[It's] Robert James\"}}</ref> (born May 14, 1989), nicknamed \"'''Gronk'''\", is an [[American football]] [[tight end]] for the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He previously played nine seasons for the [[New England Patriots]]. He is a three-time [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]], [[Super Bowl LI|LI]], [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]]), a five-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection, a four-time First Team [[All-Pro]] selection, and was selected in the [[National Football League 2010s All-Decade Team|NFL 2010s All-Decade Team]] and [[National Football League 100th Anniversary All-Time Team|NFL 100th Anniversary All-Time Team]].\n\nGronkowski played [[college football]] at the [[University of Arizona]], winning several awards, including being named a ''[[Sporting News]]'' and [[Rivals.com]] Freshman All-American. Despite only playing two collegiate seasons, his 18.8 yards per reception average and 1,197 receiving yards were a team record for his position. The Patriots drafted Gronkowski in the second round of the [[2010 NFL Draft]] with the 42nd pick, after missing his junior year due to back surgery.\n\nNotable for being a skilled [[Reception (gridiron football)|receiver]] and talented [[Blocking (American football)|blocker]], Gronkowski has set [[#NFL records|several NFL records]], including being the only one of his position to ever lead the league in receiving touchdowns (17) in 2011. He also has the most career postseason receiving yards by a tight end (1,163) \u2013 the only tight end in NFL history to reach 1,000 or more yards. He has the most career postseason receiving touchdowns for his position with 12, as well as the most combined receptions (23) and receiving yards (297) by a tight end in Super Bowl history. He is ranked first in average receiving yards per game (68.3), average yards per target (9.9), and average touchdowns per game (0.69) among tight ends.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://larrybrownsports.com/football/this-stat-rob-gronkowski-retiring-perfect-time/488952 |title=This stat shows why Rob Gronkowski is retiring at the perfect time |last=Albert |first=Darryn |date=2019-03-24 |website=Larry Brown Sports |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\nGronkowski is one of [[#Outside football|football's most popular players]], with a larger-than-life personality on and off the field. With his numerous accomplishments and accolades, he is regarded by many sports analysts, writers, and peers not only as one of his era's best players, but also [[#Football legacy|the greatest tight end to ever play the game]].<ref name=\"greatest\">{{Cite web |url=http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/here-s-why-rob-gronkowski-is-the-best-tight-end-in-nfl-history-205613222.html |title=Here's why Rob Gronkowski is the best tight end in NFL history |last=Schwab |first=Frank |website=Yahoo! Sports |language=en-CA |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150131025746/http://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/here-s-why-rob-gronkowski-is-the-best-tight-end-in-nfl-history-205613222.html |archive-date=January 13, 2015 |access-date=February 26, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Citation|title=Rob Gronkowski edges Tony Gonzalez as best tight end ever in PFT draft|date=2019-03-25|url=https://www.nbcsports.com/video/rob-gronkowski-edges-tony-gonzalez-best-tight-end-ever-pft-draft|access-date=2019-03-25}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/columnist/nate-davis/2019/03/24/rob-gronkowski-retires-new-england-patriots/3263594002/|title=Opinion: Patriots' Rob Gronkowski retires as greatest tight end in NFL history|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-25}}{{indent|3}}{{cite web |title=Shannon Sharpe: Rob Gronkowski is retiring as the most dominant tight end ever|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FOycAvq035U |website=YouTube}}{{indent|3}}{{cite web |last1=Baldinger |first1=Brian |title=The best TE (tight end) we've seen, ever. |url=https://twitter.com/NFL/status/1111327529107755008 |website=NFL}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/sports/new-england-patriots/2019/02/04/rob-gronkowski-retirement-super-bowl-pedro-martinez|title=What\u2019s Rob Gronkowski\u2019s legacy if this is truly the end?|last=|first=|date=February 4, 2019|work=Boston.com|access-date=February 19, 2019|language=en-US|quote=\"...he\u2019ll obviously go down as the best tight end to ever play in the NFL...\"}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RealSkipBayless/status/1252964944221519874|title=GOAT Gronk, the greatest TE ever.|last=Bayless|first=Skip|date=2020-04-22|website=@RealSkipBayless|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-23}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=http://www.footballperspective.com/which-patriots-will-join-brady-and-belichick-in-the-hall-of-fame/|title=Which Patriots Will Join Brady and Belichick In The Hall of Fame?|last=January 28|first=Chase Stuart on|last2=Checkdowns|first2=2019 in|date=January 28, 2019|website=FootballPerspective.com|language=en-US|access-date=February 19, 2019|quote=\"...the best tight end of all time at his peak...\"}}{{indent|3}}{{cite web |title=Jamal Adams: An absolute honor to line up and compete against the greatest Tight End ever! Congratulations to a true professional on an amazing career! |url=https://twitter.com/TheAdamsEra/status/1109988216659197953 |website=@TheAdamsEra}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/gmfb/status/1092435510692261888|title=If Gronk\u2019s last game was last night, I\u2019ll see you in five years in Canton (for Pro Football Hall of Fame). First ballot guy.|last=Schrager|first=Peter|authorlink=Peter Schrager|date=February 4, 2019|website=@gmfb|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AllbrightNFL/status/1095893239578513408|title=Gronkowski is a stone cold lock first ballot HoF (Hall of Fame).|last=Allbright|first=Benjamin|date=February 13, 2019|website=@AllbrightNFL|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/NFL_DovKleiman/status/1096027220055900161|title=...the best player ever in his position, who also happened to win 3 Superbowls...|last=Kleiman|first=Dov|date=February 14, 2019|website=@NFL_DovKleiman|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/chatham58/status/1096036432903315456|title=Gronk is the best that\u2019s ever played TE\u2014it\u2019s not even close.|last=Chatham|first=Matt|authorlink=Matt Chatham|date=February 14, 2019|website=@chatham58|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/maxkellerman/status/1092249607483154434|title=#Gronk is the greatest TE of all time. #SBLlll|last=Kellerman|first=Max|authorlink=Max Kellerman|date=February 3, 2019|website=@maxkellerman|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TampaBayTre/status/1095889353124036614|title=Gronkowski is the greatest tight end to ever play the game|last=Sikkema|first=Trevor|date=February 13, 2019|website=@TampaBayTre|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mikefreemanNFL/status/1095891473311113217|title=He\u2019s the best TE of all time|last=Freeman|first=Mike|authorlink=Mike Freeman (columnist)|date=February 13, 2019|website=@mikefreemanNFL|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TheKostos/status/1095892337635545089|title=Gronk is the best TE ever|last=Kostos|first=Nick|date=February 13, 2019|website=@TheKostos|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ConnorJRogers/status/1095885967913877504|title=...literally the greatest TE of all time.|last=Rogers|first=Connor|date=February 13, 2019|website=@ConnorJRogers|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Dameshek/status/942802466722082819|title=One thing that's beyond dispute: Gronk's the best to ever play his position|last=Dameshek|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Dameshek|date=December 18, 2017|website=@Dameshek|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019}}{{indent|3}}{{Cite web|url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2019/02/14/hall-of-fame-hypocrisy-rob-gronkowski-debate/|title=Hall Of Fame Hypocrisy Continues With New Rob Gronkowski First-Ballot Debate|last=|first=|date=February 14, 2019|website=|language=en|access-date=February 19, 2019|quote=\"There\u2019s been no more dominant tight end in the history of the sport.\"}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nGronkowski<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hanzus|first1=Dan|title=Gronk pines for wife who cooks, cleans, makes big cash|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000482857/article/gronk-pines-for-wife-who-cooks-cleans-makes-big-cash|publisher=NFL|date=March 31, 2015|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> was born in [[Amherst, New York]], on May 14, 1989, and was later raised in [[Williamsville, New York|Williamsville]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/robgronkowski/497240/profile|title=Rob Gronkowski|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref> He is the second youngest son of Gordon Gronkowski and Diane Walters, and is of [[Poles|Polish descent]] through his father.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.naplesnews.com/story/news/archive/2018/02/04/rob-gronkowskis-mother-fort-myers-resident-raised-some-big-boys/304938002/ | title=Rob Gronkowski's mother, a Fort Myers resident, raised some big boys | first=Craig | last=Handel | date=February 4, 2018 | work=Naples Daily News | language=en | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.si.com/vault/2012/09/03/106228989/the-last-happy-man | title=The Last Happy Man | last=Ballard | first=Chris | date=September 3, 2012 | work=Sports Illustrated | language=en | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> His father is a former college football guard for [[Syracuse Orange football|Syracuse University]] who later founded a high-end fitness equipment business.<ref>{{Citation|last=Chase|title=Rob Gronkowski Talks About His Financial Plays {{!}} Kneading Dough S.2, E.4|date=August 24, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n2rMafJgoZg|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> He is a great-grandson of [[Ignatius Gronkowski]] who represented the United States in [[cycling]] at the [[1924 Summer Olympics]] in [[Paris]], [[France]], and held five world records in the sport.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://usbhof.org/patriots-star-gronkowskis-great-grandfather-was-olympic-cyclist/ | title=Patriots Star Gronkowski\u2019s Great Grandfather Was Olympic Cyclist | last=Bowen | first=Bob | date=January 19, 2018 | publisher=U.S. Bicycling Hall of Fame | language=en-US | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> Gronkowski's parents divorced in 2008.<ref name=\":0\" /> His four brothers \u2013 Gordie, [[Dan Gronkowski|Dan]], [[Chris Gronkowski|Chris]] and [[Glenn Gronkowski|Glenn]] \u2013 all played collegiate sports, and later played professionally.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://thesouthern.com/news/local/pats-tight-end-almost-played-for-miners/article_2932d2de-4fb6-11e1-862c-001871e3ce6c.html | title=Pats' tight end almost played for Miners | first=Scott | last=Mees | date=February 5, 2012 | work=The Southern Illinoisan | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"dan\">{{cite web|url=http://umterps.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/gronkowski_dan00.html|title=Player Bio: Dan Gronkowski|work=[[Maryland Terrapins|University of Maryland Athletics]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090105074932/http://umterps.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/gronkowski_dan00.html|archivedate=January 5, 2009|url-status=dead|accessdate=January 12, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000162818/article/san-diego-chargers-sign-fullback-chris-gronkowski | title=San Diego Chargers sign fullback Chris Gronkowski | agency=Associated Press | date=April 23, 2013 | publisher=NFL.com | accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000712872/article/patriots-add-glenn-gronkowski-to-practice-squad | title=Patriots add Glenn Gronkowski to practice squad | first=Jeremy | last=Bergman | date=October 1, 2016 | publisher=NFL.com | accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGronkowski played [[Ice hockey|hockey]] until he was 14; he then started playing [[basketball]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2015/12/31/no-surprise-rob-gronkowski-super-aggressive-when-he-played-hockey/ | title=No surprise: Rob Gronkowski 'super aggressive' when he played hockey | first=Karen | last=Guregian | date=December 31, 2015 | work=Boston Herald | accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref> He attended [[Williamsville North High School]] for three years, playing [[tight end]] and [[defensive end]] (and freshman [[kickoff specialist]], on account of having the biggest feet on the team), [[Center (basketball)|center]] in basketball, and [[first baseman]] in [[baseball]] for the Spartans athletic teams.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2018/01/26/super-bowl-52-rob-gronkowski-patriots-buffalo-area-williamsville-north-high-school-tradavious-white-hit | title=Rob Gronkowski In High School: A Dominant Athlete, But Keep an Eye on the Gronk-O-Meter | first=Jenny | last=Vrentas | date=January 26, 2018 | work=Sports Illustrated | access-date=March 27, 2019 | language=en}}</ref> As a junior playing football, he recorded 36 receptions for 648 yards and seven touchdowns on offense, and 73 tackles and six sacks on defense. He was named an All-Western New York first-team and All-State second-team player.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=https://arizonawildcats.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=147 |title=Player Bio: Rob Gronkowski |publisher=[[University of Arizona]] |accessdate=September 23, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100703225155/http://www.arizonawildcats.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/gronkowski_rob00.html |archivedate=July 3, 2010  }}</ref> Academically, Gronkowski was in the [[National Honor Society]], citing math as his best subject, and English the worst.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://dujour.com/lifestyle/rob-gronkowski-patriots-pictures-interview/ | title=It's Great to Be Gronk | first=Lindsay | last=Silberman | date=June 1, 2015 | work=DuJour | language=en-US | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Gronkowski moved to [[Pittsburgh metropolitan area|suburban Pittsburgh]], where he attended [[Woodland Hills High School]] for his senior year. Initially ruled ineligible by the [[Western Pennsylvania Interscholastic Athletic League]] because of his transfer,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/06234/715337-49.stm|title=WPIAL benches high school football transfer|work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=August 26, 2006|accessdate=November 17, 2010|first=Mike|last=White}}</ref> he recorded eight receptions for 152 yards and four touchdowns at Woodland Hills after the ruling of ineligibility was overturned. He was named a SuperPrep All-American, [[PrepStar]] All-American, [[Associated Press]] Class 4-A all-state, ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' \"Fabulous 22\", ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette'' first-team all-conference, ''[[The Patriot-News]]'' ([[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania]]) \"Platinum 33\", and a ''[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]'' \"Terrific 25\" player.<ref name=bio/> He was recruited by [[Kentucky Wildcats football|Kentucky]], [[Arizona Wildcats football|Arizona]], [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson]], [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]], [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]], [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]], and [[Syracuse Orangemen football|Syracuse]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://recruiting.scout.com/a.z?s=73&p=8&c=1&nid=2138007|title=Rob Gronkowski Profile|work=[[Scout.com]]|accessdate=April 30, 2009}}</ref> Gronkowski graduated from Woodland Hills in 2007 with a 3.75 [[Grading in education|GPA]] and 1560 [[SAT]] score.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/ENE8oKDXUAA1LES.jpg|title=Scholar Athlete Banquet|last=|first=|date=2007|website=The Total Media|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== College career ==\nAfter graduating from high school, Gronkowski attended the [[University of Arizona]] as a Pre-Business major and played for the [[Arizona Wildcats football]] team from 2007 to 2009 under head coach [[Mike Stoops]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/rob-gronkowski-1.html |title=Rob Gronkowski College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/arizona/coaches.html |title=Arizona Wildcats Coaches |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> As a freshman in 2007, he recorded 28 receptions for 525 yards and six touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/rob-gronkowski-1/gamelog/2007/ |title=Rob Gronkowski 2007 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> His 18.8 yards per reception average was the best on the team and his receiving yards were a school record for a tight end. He was named  ''[[The Sporting News]]'' freshman All-American, [[Rivals.com]] freshman All-American, ''The Sporting News'' freshman [[Pac-10 Conference|Pac-10]], and All-Pac-10 honorable mention player.<ref name=bio/>\n\nGronkowski missed the first three games of the [[2008 Arizona Wildcats football team|2008 season]], but later recorded 47 receptions for 672 yards and a team-best ten touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/arizona/2008.html |title=2008 Arizona Wildcats Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/rob-gronkowski-1/gamelog/2008/ |title=Rob Gronkowski 2008 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> Five of his touchdowns were scored in his first two games against [[2008 UCLA Bruins football team|UCLA]] and [[2008 Washington Huskies football team|Washington]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-09-20-ucla.html |title=Arizona at UCLA Box Score, September 20, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2008-10-04-arizona.html |title=Washington at Arizona Box Score, October 4, 2008 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> He was twice named the [[John Mackey (American football)|John Mackey]] National Tight End of the Week, including his performance in a failed comeback bid against [[2008 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon]], when he caught 12 passes for 143 yards. He set the school records for a tight end for single-game, single-season, and career receptions, yards, and touchdowns. Gronkowski was named an Associated Press third-team [[2008 College Football All-America Team|All-American]] and All-Pac-10 first-team tight end.<ref name=bio/>\n\nPrior to the 2009 season, Gronkowski was placed on the watchlist for the [[Lombardi Award]], which is awarded to the most outstanding college football lineman or linebacker.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arizonaathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/030209aaa.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120721222823/http://www.arizonaathletics.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/030209aaa.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 21, 2012|title=Gronkowski on Early National Radar|work=[[University of Arizona]]|date=March 2, 2009|accessdate=April 27, 2010}}</ref> He missed his junior season in 2009 due to back surgery, which caused his draft stock to fall.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.weei.com/sports/boston/football/patriots/ryan-hannable/2016/09/14/latest-rob-gronkowski-injury-reminder-appre |title=Latest Rob Gronkowski injury reminder to appreciate what he does now, as he can't last forever |date=September 15, 2016 |website=WEEI |url-status=dead |access-date=November 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center; font-weight:bold; background-color:#cc0033; color:#ffffff;\"|Rob Gronkowski<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/rob-gronkowski-1.html|title=Rob Gronkowski College Stats &#124; College Football at|date=January 1, 1970|publisher=Sports-reference.com|accessdate=April 24, 2017}}</ref>!! colspan=\"3\" | Receiving\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! GP !! Rec !! Yards !! TDs\n|-\n| [[2007 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2007]] || [[2007 Arizona Wildcats football team|Arizona]]\n| 12 || 28 || 525 || 6\n|-\n| [[2008 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2008]] || [[2008 Arizona Wildcats football team|Arizona]]\n| 10 || 47 || 672 || 10\n|- style=\"background:#555; font-weight:bold; color:white;\"\n| colspan=\"2\"|Total || 22 || 75 || 1,197 || 16\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n===New England Patriots===\n{{quote box\n| align = right\n| width = 28%\n| quote = \"So Rob Gronkowski, certainly an interesting player. Excellent size, very well thought of down there by Coach [Mike] Stoops and his staff. I think as we saw there, in New York, he\u2019s kind of a fun loving guy who enjoys having a good time, but he plays like that, too. He plays with a good attitude. He\u2019s aggressive.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nesn.com/2010/05/rob-gronkowskis-draft-day-antics-will-translate-well-to-football-field/ |title=Rob Gronkowski\u2019s Draft-Day Emotions Will Translate Well to Football Field for Patriots |last=Howe |first=Jeff |date=May 11, 2010 |website=NESN |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n<br>\u2013Coach [[Bill Belichick]], April 2010\n}}Gronkowski was drafted by the [[New England Patriots]] in the second round (42nd overall) of the [[2010 NFL Draft]], after a draft day trade with the [[Oakland Raiders]]; in pre-draft evaluations revealed in May 2016, Raiders scouts had rated Gronkowski as the \"best all-around player in the draft\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://weei.radio.com/blogs/unearthed-pre-draft-evaluations-2010-reveal-raiders-thought-rob-gronkowski-was-best-all-around |title=Unearthed pre-draft evaluations from 2010 reveal Raiders thought Rob Gronkowski was \u2018best all-around player in the draft\u2019 |date=May 9, 2016 |website=It Is What It Is |language=en-US |access-date=May 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2010/draft.htm|title=2010 NFL Draft Listing|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> He signed a four-year contract on July 25, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4680302/gronkowski-signs-rookie-deal|title=Gronkowski signs rookie deal|last=Reiss|first=Mike|date=July 25, 2010|work=ESPNBoston.com|accessdate=July 25, 2010}}</ref> The deal was worth $4.4 million, with a $1.76 million signing bonus.{{nfl predraft\n| height ft = 6\n| height in = 6\u00bc\n| weight = 258\n| dash = 4.68\n| ten split = 1.58\n| twenty split = 2.68\n| shuttle = 4.47\n| cone drill = 7.18\n| vertical = 33\u00bd\n| broad ft = 9\n| broad in = 11\n| bench = 23\n| wonderlic = 32<ref>{{cite web|url=https://imgur.com/gallery/qs5YNC9|title=Wonderlic'in Good!|first=|last=Imgur|website=Imgur}}</ref>\n| arm span = 34\u00bc\n| hand span = 10\u00be\n| note = All values from Arizona Pro Day,<ref name=Workout>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=70168&draftyear=2010&genpos=TE|title=*Rob Gronkowski - Arizona, TE : 2010 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref> except measurements and BP (from the [[NFL Combine]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/rob-gronkowski?id=497240|title=NFL Events: Combine Player Profiles - Rob Gronkowski|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref> Did not participate in most combine events due to a back injury.<ref name=Workout />\n}}\n{{external media|width=285px|video1=[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-draft/09000d5d817be425/Patriots-pick-Rob-Gronkowski 2010 NFL Draft: Rob Gronkowski]|video2=[http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-videos/09000d5d8177eae1/2010-Draft-Vignettes-Rob-Gronkowski-Arizona 2010 NFL Draft Vignette: Rob Gronkowski]}}\n\n====2010 season====\nDuring the preseason, Gronkowski was one of three NFL players to score four touchdowns, tying [[Victor Cruz (American football)|Victor Cruz]], a rookie [[wide receiver]] for the [[New York Giants]], and [[Anthony Dixon]], a [[running back]] for the [[San Francisco 49ers]]. In the [[2010 New England Patriots season|Week 1]] game against the [[2010 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], Gronkowski caught his first regular season touchdown in the fourth quarter on a one-yard pass from [[Tom Brady]] in the 38\u201324 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009120nwe.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at New England Patriots - September 12th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn a Week 10 victory over the [[2010 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Gronkowski caught three touchdown passes from Brady, becoming the first rookie in Patriots history, and the youngest rookie in NFL history to accomplish the feat.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201011140pit.htm |title=New England Patriots at Pittsburgh Steelers - November 14th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/L38AM |title=Youngest rookies to record three touchdowns receptions in a single game, NFL history |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=November 17, 2010}}</ref> In honor of the feat, ''[[Madden NFL 12]]'' has a \"Rob Gronkowski Award\" for players who have a tight end catch three or more touchdowns in a single game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.trueachievements.com/a153242/rob-gronkowski-award-achievement |title=Rob Gronkowski Award Achievement in Madden NFL 12 |website=TrueAchievements |language=en |access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\nVisiting his hometown of Buffalo in Week 16, Gronkowski caught two touchdowns against the [[2010 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], and added a touchdown in the season finale to give him 10 on the season; in 16 games played (11 starts), Gronkowski caught 42 passes for 546 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201012260buf.htm |title=New England Patriots at Buffalo Bills - December 26th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GronRo00/gamelog/2010/ |title=Rob Gronkowski 2010 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> Despite missing his entire 2009 college season following back surgery, Gronkowski did not miss a single game or practice all season;<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/boston/nfl/columns/story?columnist=reiss_mike&id=6085654 |title=Like Mark Bavaro, New England Patriots TE Rob Gronkowski fits coach Bill Belichick's mold - ESPN Boston |last=Reiss |first=Mike |date=February 3, 2011 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 28, 2012}}</ref> he was the first rookie tight end since the [[NFL-AFL merger]] to score 10 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://chowderandchampions.com/2020/03/25/new-england-patriots-7-best-players-tom-brady-threw-tds-career/7/ |title=New England Patriots: 7 best players Tom Brady threw TD\u2019s to over his career |date=2020-03-25 |website=Chowder and Champions |language=en-US |access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> The Patriots finished with 14\u20132 record and won the [[AFC East]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2010.htm |title=2010 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In the playoffs, Gronkowski made his postseason debut against the [[2010 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] in the [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs#AFC: New York Jets 28, New England Patriots 21|Divisional Round]]. In the 28\u201321 upset loss, he had four receptions for 65 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101160nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - New York Jets at New England Patriots - January 16th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGronkowski was nominated three times for [[Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Week]], in Weeks 10, 14, and 17, winning twice and losing in Week 10 to [[Tim Tebow]]. Gronkowski also finished fifth in fan balloting at tight end for the [[2011 Pro Bowl]], and fourth overall among rookies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/BostonNew-England-Patriots/post/_/id/4690273/where-pats-rank-in-fan-pro-bowl-voting|title=Where Pats rank in fan Pro Bowl voting|work=ESPNBoston.com|first=Mike|last=Reiss|date=December 22, 2010|accessdate=December 22, 2010}}</ref> Gronkowski also received one writer's vote for the Associated Press [[2010 All-Pro Team]] (writers only vote for one tight end).\n\n====2011 season====\n[[File:Colts vs Patriots 2011 01.jpg|thumb|Gronkowski (#87) in a 2011 game against the [[Indianapolis Colts]]]]\nGronkowski caught his first touchdown of the 2011 season on a 10-yard pass from Tom Brady in the Patriots' Week 1 victory over the [[2011 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]]; Gronkowski's six catches accounted for 86 of Brady's franchise record 517 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109120mia.htm |title=New England Patriots at Miami Dolphins - September 12th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In Week 11, against the [[2011 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], Gronkowski caught two touchdown passes, including a career-long 52-yard catch and run, to equal his 2010 touchdown total in just ten games; he passed his reception and yardage totals from 2010 in only eight games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111210nwe.htm |title=Kansas City Chiefs at New England Patriots - November 21st, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThrough Week 11, Gronkowski led all tight ends with 10 touchdowns; his 20 touchdowns were the most ever for a tight end in his first two seasons. His reception and receiving yardage totals both ranked second among tight ends (after [[Jimmy Graham]] of the [[New Orleans Saints]]), and in the top ten among all receivers, though they only ranked second on the Patriots, behind wide receiver [[Wes Welker]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2011.htm |title=2011 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nGronkowski broke the NFL record for touchdowns scored in a single season by a tight end when he had the second three-touchdown game of his career in the Patriots' Week 13 victory against the [[2011 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]]. After scoring two touchdowns on receptions from Tom Brady, Gronkowski scored a third touchdown from two yards out. Initially declared a forward pass, the pass was later ruled a [[lateral pass]],<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/7316751/rob-gronkowski-finds-new-way-reach-end-zone |title=Rob Gronkowski finds new way to reach end zone - ESPN Boston |last=Forsberg |first=Chris |date=December 4, 2011 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 28, 2012}}</ref> which is recorded as a rushing attempt; it was the only rushing attempt of Gronkowski's career, and his only rushing touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112040nwe.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots - December 4th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> It was also the first rushing touchdown by a tight end since [[Bo Scaife]] did it in 2006,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> and the first in Patriots history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bostonglobe.com/sports/2011/12/05/rob-gronkowski-track-one-nfl-greatest/grjZASYeVzbnmJO7AGLs5O/story.html|title=Rob Gronkowski on track to be one of NFL's greatest|newspaper=The Boston Globe|date=December 5, 2011|accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref> At game's end, Gronkowski had sole possession of the touchdown scoring record, with 14, and shared the record for ''receiving'' touchdowns, 13, with [[Antonio Gates]] and [[Vernon Davis]].\n\nGronkowski took sole possession of the tight end receiving record a week later against the [[2011 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], in which he caught his 14th and 15th touchdown passes of the season; in total, he had six receptions for a career-high 160 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112110was.htm |title=New England Patriots at Washington Redskins - December 11th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> His performance also earned him his first AFC Offensive Player of the Week award,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/boston/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4712242/gronk-earns-afc-player-of-week-honor |title=Gronk earns AFC player of week honor - New England Patriots Blog |last=Reiss |first=Mike |date=December 14, 2011 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 28, 2012}}</ref> and, for the second week in a row, NFL.com's \"Hardest Working Man\" award.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/new-england-patriots/09000d5d8251eb9b/Week-14-Hardest-Working-Man-winner|title=NFL Videos: Week 14: Hardest Working Man winner|publisher=Nfl.com|date=December 16, 2011|accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref> He ended the season with 1,327 receiving yards, breaking the previous NFL record for a tight end of 1,310 set by [[Jimmy Graham]] of the Saints earlier that same day.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/7411087/new-england-patriots-rob-gronkowski-breaks-tight-end-yardage-record|title=Rob Gronkowski sets TE yardage mark|last=|first=|date=January 1, 2012|work=ESPNBoston.com|access-date=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120102055511/http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/7411087/new-england-patriots-rob-gronkowski-breaks-tight-end-yardage-record|archivedate=January 2, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> He also finished with 18 total touchdowns, 17 receiving\u2014both NFL records for tight ends. Gronkowski's 18 touchdowns were the second-highest total in the NFL (after Philadelphia's [[LeSean McCoy]], who had 20), and equaled the output of the entire [[2011 St. Louis Rams season|St. Louis Rams]] team. His 17 receiving touchdowns were the most of any NFL player in 2011, marking the first time in NFL history a tight end had sole possession of the league lead.\n\nGronkowski was voted the starting tight end for the AFC at the [[2012 Pro Bowl]]. One of eight Patriots players voted to the Pro Bowl, he finished fan voting with 936,886 votes, more than triple the number received by the number two tight end, Gronkowski's teammate [[Aaron Hernandez]], and the third-highest total of any AFC player, behind teammates [[Tom Brady]] and [[Wes Welker]]. He was also voted the tight end for the AP [[2011 All-Pro Team|All-Pro]] first team, receiving 44\u00bd of the 50 votes (44 voters voted for Gronkowski; 5 voters voted for [[Jimmy Graham]], and one voter split a vote between the two).<ref>{{cite web|last=Kuharsky|first=Paul|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/afcsouth/post/_/id/32971/all-pro-voting-totals|title=All-Pro voting totals - AFC South Blog|publisher=Espn.go.com|date=January 2, 2011|accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2011 postseason====\nIn the Patriots' first playoff game, a 45\u201310 rout of the [[2011 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] in the [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 45, Denver Broncos 10|Divisional Round]], Gronkowski tied an NFL post-season record, catching three touchdown passes as part of a 10-catch, 145-yard effort. Gronkowski alone had more catches than the entire Broncos offense, as quarterback [[Tim Tebow]] completed just 9 of 26 passes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201140nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Denver Broncos at New England Patriots - January 14th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 23, Baltimore Ravens 20|AFC Championship]], a 23\u201320 win over the [[2011 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], Gronkowski suffered a [[high ankle sprain]] on a tackle by Ravens safety [[Bernard Pollard]]; the status of his ankle was one of the major story lines in the run-up to [[Super Bowl XLVI]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nj.com/giants/index.ssf/2012/02/patriots_rob_gronkowski_is_lim.html |title=Patriots' Rob Gronkowski is limited by ankle injury in Super Bowl loss to Giants |last=Vrentas |first=Jenny |date=February 6, 2012 |website=NJ.com |language=en-US |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref> Gronkowski still managed to finish with five receptions for 87 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201220nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship - Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots - January 22nd, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In Super Bowl XLVI, the Patriots decided to start Gronkowski, but he wasn't a large factor in the game. With only a few seconds left in the Super Bowl XLVI, Gronkowski had a chance on Tom Brady's Hail Mary as time expired, but his dive for the ball came up short. Gronkowski finished the game with two receptions for 26 yards, which was his lowest output since early October. The Patriots lost the Super Bowl to the [[2011 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], 21\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201202050nwe.htm |title=Super Bowl XLVI - New York Giants vs. New England Patriots - February 5th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/02/05/sport/super-bowl |title=Super Bowl XLVI as it happened |last=Gittings |first=Paul |date=February 6, 2012 |work=CNN.com |access-date=December 26, 2019}}</ref> A few days after the Super Bowl, Gronkowski had an MRI of his injured ankle that revealed strained ligaments and required surgery to repair.\n\n====2012 season====\n[[File:Rob Gronkowski 2013.jpg|thumbnail|upright|Gronkowski during the 2013 season]]\nOn June 8, 2012, Gronkowski signed a six-year, $54 million contract extension, the largest ever for an NFL tight end. The contract included an $8 million signing bonus, but otherwise left the 2012 and 2013 seasons of his rookie contract intact.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Aaron|title=Rob Gronkowski gets six-year, $54 million contract extension|url=http://profootball.scout.com/a.z?s=127&p=9&c=2&cid=1193260&nid=6307354&fhn=1|accessdate=June 8, 2012}}</ref> Gronkowski broke his left forearm late in the fourth quarter during an extra point in the Patriots' 59\u201324 victory in Week 11 over the [[2012 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]].<ref>[http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/8651806/rob-gronkowski-new-england-patriots-surgery-arm-source ESPN.com]. Retrieved November 19, 2012.</ref> Before doing so, however, he became the third tight end in NFL history (after [[Tony Gonzalez]] and [[Antonio Gates]]) to achieve three seasons with at least 10 touchdown receptions, and the first ever to do it in consecutive seasons. Gronkowski returned to practice in Week 15, and participated in the Week 17 game against the [[2012 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], scoring a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201212300nwe.htm |title=Miami Dolphins at New England Patriots - December 30th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> He re-injured his left arm in the first quarter of the Patriots' first playoff game, against the [[2012 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]]. He required another operation, and missed the remainder of the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/8841038/2013-nfl-playoffs-rob-gronkowski-new-england-patriots-miss-rest-postseason-due-broken-arm-sources|title=Sources: Gronkowski (arm) done for playoffs|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=November 2, 2016}}</ref> In 11 games in the 2012 season, Gronkowski had 790 receiving yards and 11 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GronRo00/gamelog/2012/ |title=Rob Gronkowski 2012 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rob Gronkowski 20131201.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Gronkowski in 2013]]\n\n====2013 season====\nIn February 2013, Gronkowski was diagnosed with an infection in his forearm. He underwent an open procedure\u2014the third on his forearm\u2014in an effort to clear the infection; he was subsequently placed on a course of antibiotics. On May 20, 2013, Gronkowski underwent a fourth surgery on his forearm to replace the hardware implanted in the second procedure and perform tissue biopsies. ESPN's [[Adam Schefter]] reported that doctors were encouraged the infection had finally resolved. On June 18, 2013, Gronkowski underwent back surgery.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/patriots-te-gronkowski-undergoes-back-surgery-000336414.html |title=Patriots TE Gronkowski undergoes back surgery |date=June 18, 2013 |website=Yahoo! News |access-date=July 5, 2013 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He was cleared to play for the October 20, 2013, game against the [[2013 New York Jets season|New York Jets]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Patriots' Gronkowski cleared to play vs. Jets|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/patriots/2013/10/18/new-england-patriots-growkowski-cleared-to-play-against-new-york-jets/3007751/?dlvrit=206567|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=October 18, 2013|first1=Tom|last1=Pelissero|date=October 18, 2013}}</ref> During a game against the [[2013 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]] on December 8, 2013, Gronkowski suffered a right knee injury after a direct hit from safety [[T. J. Ward]].<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/nfl/story/_/id/10103044/rob-gronkowski-new-england-patriots-carted-leg-injury |title=Rob Gronkowski may have ACL tear |publisher=ESPN.com |date=December 8, 2013 |accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref> Gronkowski [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|tore his ACL]] and [[Medial collateral ligament|MCL]], which prematurely ended his 2013 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/nfl/story/_/id/10108168/rob-gronkowski-new-england-patriots-tears-acl-mcl-knee|title=Rob Gronkowski out; tears ACL, MCL|publisher=ESPN.com|date=December 9, 2013|accessdate=December 9, 2013}}</ref> In seven games, Gronkowski produced 592 receiving yards and four receiving touchdowns in six starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GronRo00/gamelog/2013/ |title=Rob Gronkowski 2013 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\nIn his first game back from ACL/MCL surgery, Gronkowski managed to catch four passes for 40 receiving yards and a receiving touchdown against the [[2014 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] in a losing effort, 33\u201320.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070mia.htm |title=New England Patriots at Miami Dolphins - September 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> He played on limited snaps as the Patriots worked him back to full strength slowly. Against the [[2014 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] in Week 2, Gronkowski had four receptions for 32 receiving yards in a 30\u20137 win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409140min.htm |title=New England Patriots at Minnesota Vikings - September 14th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> Against the [[2014 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]] in Week 3, Gronkowski had three receptions for 44 yards and his second touchdown of the season, and the only touchdown scored in the Patriots' 16\u20139 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409210nwe.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at New England Patriots - September 21st, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> Through Week 3, Gronkowski logged one start, 11 receptions, 116 receiving yards, and two receiving touchdowns on only 109 offensive snaps (42% of the team's offensive total). Gronkowski broke out in Week 8 against the [[2014 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], catching nine passes for 149 yards and three receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201410260nwe.htm |title=Chicago Bears at New England Patriots - October 26th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In Week 14 against the [[2014 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]], Gronkowski became the first tight end in NFL history to catch at least 10 touchdowns in four separate seasons. In the game, he had eight receptions for 87 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201412070sdg.htm |title=New England Patriots at San Diego Chargers - December 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> The Patriots finished with a 12\u20134 record and won the AFC East.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2014.htm |title=2014 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 35, Baltimore Ravens 31|Divisional Round]] against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], he had seven receptions for 108 yards and a touchdown in the 35\u201331 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501100nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Baltimore Ravens at New England Patriots - January 10th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 45, Indianapolis Colts 7|AFC Championship]] against the [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he had three receptions for 28 yards and a touchdown in the 45\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501180nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship - Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots - January 18th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> Gronkowski was a major factor in the Patriots' 28-24 [[Super Bowl XLIX]] win over the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], recording 6 catches for 68 yards and a touchdown late in the second quarter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tom Brady and Rob Gronkowski Roll Into the Record Books|url=http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/extra_points/2014/10/tom_brady_and_rob_gronkowski_roll_into_the_record.html|accessdate=October 27, 2014|work=The Boston Globe}}</ref> Gronkowski was fined twice this season, once for \"unnecessary roughness\" against Indianapolis Colts safety [[Sergio Brown]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gantt|first1=Dan|title=Rob Gronkowski fined $8,268 for bouncer move|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2014/11/21/rob-gronkowski-fined-8268-for-bouncer-move/|website=ESPN|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> and the other time occurring during Super Bowl XLIX. Gronkowski, among three others, was fined $8,628 for \"striking an opponent\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Reiss|first1=Mike|title=Bruce Irvin fined $10K for scuffle|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/12289724/bruce-irvin-michael-bennett-rob-gronkowski-michael-hoomanawanui-fined-super-bowl-xlix-fight-seattle-seahawks-new-england-patriots|website=ESPN|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nGronkowski was named to his third [[Pro Bowl]] and was the unanimous choice for tight end on the [[2014 All-Pro Team]], receiving all 50 votes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/probowl.htm |title=2014 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/allpro.htm |title=2014 NFL All-Pros |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref> At the [[2015 ESPY Awards]], Gronkowski won the Comeback Player of the Year award for his 2014 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://boston.cbslocal.com/2015/07/16/rob-gronkowski-wins-comeback-player-of-the-year-espy/ |title=Rob Gronkowski Wins Comeback Player Of The Year ESPY |date=July 16, 2015 |language=en |access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2015 season====\n[[File:President Barack Obama jokes with Rob Gronkowski.jpg|thumb|Gronkowski with then US President [[Barack Obama]] at an event to honor the team and their [[Super Bowl XLIX]] victory, at the White House on April 23, 2015.|266x266px]]\n\nDuring the Patriots' [[Kickoff Classic|home opener]] on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' against the [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]] on September 10, 2015, Gronkowski caught five passes for 94 yards, scoring three of the Patriots' four touchdowns in their 28\u201321 victory.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rosenthal|first1=Gregg|title=Gronkowski, Patriots put on familiar show in 28-21 victory over Steelers.|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000525750/article/rob-gronkowski-patriots-put-on-familiar-show|website=www.nfl.com|publisher=NFL|access-date=September 10, 2015}}</ref> The three-touchdown performance was the third in Gronkowski's career, one shy of wide receiver [[Randy Moss]]'s team record of four. It also made Gronkowski the first player in NFL history with multiple three-touchdown-reception games against the Steelers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lefort|first1=David|title=Rob Gronkowski unstoppable against Steelers|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4785037/rob-gronkowski-scores-patriots-first-two-touchdowns-of-season|website=www.espn.go.com|publisher=ESPN|access-date=September 10, 2015}}</ref> Through the Patriots' first six games, all victories, Gronkowski recorded 34 receptions for 533 yards and six touchdowns.<ref name=\"yahooProfile\">{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/players/24017/|title=Rob Gronkowski - New England Patriots - National Football League - Yahoo! Sports|author=|date=|publisher=|access-date=November 2, 2016}}</ref> He added 113 yards and a touchdown on October 29 in a 36\u20137 win over the [[2015 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/miami-dolphins-new-england-patriots-20151029017/|title=Miami at New England - 2015-10-29 - National Football League - Yahoo! Sports|author=|date=|publisher=Yahoo|access-date=November 2, 2016}}</ref> In the Patriots' first loss of the season, on November 29, 2015, against the [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], Gronkowski had to be carted off the field after a right knee injury in the fourth quarter. Initial reports said that the injury appeared to be less serious than it originally looked.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000591229/article/rob-gronkowski-carted-off-field-after-injuring-knee |title=Rob Gronkowski carted off field after injuring knee |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter missing a week, Gronkowski returned for the Patriots' December 13 game against the [[2015 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]]. He caught four passes for 87 yards and a touchdown, for a total of 10 touchdowns and 1,018 yards on the season.<ref name=\"yahooProfile\"/> The Patriots won, 27\u20136, to snap a two-game losing streak.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512130htx.htm |title=New England Patriots at Houston Texans - December 13th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, Gronkowski caught five passes for 54 yards and one touchdown in a 33\u201316 win over the [[2015 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201512200nwe.htm |title=Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots - December 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> He dedicated the touchdown to his friend Dana Parenteau, who had died at the age of 43 two days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2015/12/20/rob-gronkowski-dedicates-win-over-titans-late-friend/qkJDbP8ZPdYMMsfxBYsTdO/story.html|title=Rob Gronkowski dedicates win over Titans to late friend - The Boston Globe|newspaper=Boston Globe|access-date=November 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the Patriots' 27\u201320 win over the [[2015 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] in the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 27, Kansas City Chiefs 20|Divisional Round]], Gronkowski caught seven passes for 83 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601160nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Kansas City Chiefs at New England Patriots - January 16th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2015\u201316 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 20, New England Patriots 18|AFC Championship]], a 20\u201318 loss to the Denver Broncos, Gronkowski led all receivers with eight catches for 144 yards and a receiving touchdown. Gronkowski had the Patriots' final touchdown to put the Patriots within two points, but the resulting two-point conversion was unsuccessful.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201601240den.htm |title=AFC Championship - New England Patriots at Denver Broncos - January 24th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/new-england-patriots-denver-broncos-20160124007/|title=New England at Denver - 2016-01-24 - National Football League - Yahoo! Sports|author=|date=|publisher=Yahoo|access-date=November 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\nGronkowski was selected to the [[2016 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] and to the [[2015 All-Pro Team|AP All-Pro first team]] for the fourth time in his career; he led all non-quarterbacks in fan voting for the Pro Bowl, and received 48 of 50 All-Pro votes at tight end.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/kansas-city-chiefs-new-england-patriots-20160116017/|title=Kansas City at New England - 2016-01-16 - National Football League - Yahoo! Sports|author=|date=|publisher=Yahoo|access-date=November 2, 2016}}</ref> He was ranked as the ninth best player on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000673250/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-9-Rob-Gronkowski |title=NFL Top 100 Players of 2016 - No. 9 Rob Gronkowski |publisher=Nfl.com |date= |accessdate=April 24, 2017}}he retired on an Instagram post on March 24, 2019</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\nGronkowski missed the first two games of the 2016 season due to a hamstring injury and was limited in his next two games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000715888/article/rob-gronkowski-hamstring-has-obviously-limited-me |title=Rob Gronkowski: Hamstring has 'obviously' limited me |publisher=NFL.com |date=July 29, 2013 |accessdate=April 24, 2017}}</ref> Against the [[2016 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]] in Week 8, Gronkowski scored the 69th regular-season touchdown of his career, which was also his 68th receiving touchdown. The touchdown broke both Patriots franchise records set by [[Stanley Morgan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/10/30/rob-gronkowski-sets-patriots-franchise-record-with-69th-touchdown/|title=Rob Gronkowski Sets Patriots Franchise Record With 69th Touchdown |access-date=October 30, 2016}}</ref> In Week 10 against the [[2016 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], he took a big hit to the chest by [[Earl Thomas (defensive back)|Earl Thomas]] which was initially thought to be a punctured lung but turned out to be a [[pulmonary contusion]], keeping him out in Week 11.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rob Gronkowski suffered possible punctured lung |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000739824/article/rob-gronkowski-suffered-possible-punctured-lung |author=Rosenthal, Gregg |website=NFL.com |date=November 14, 2016 |accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref> In Week 12 against the [[2016 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], he suffered a back injury at the beginning of the second half, which needed surgery to repair a herniated disk, and was out for the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rob Gronkowski to undergo back surgery Friday |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000749361/article/patriots-gronkowski-to-undergo-back-surgery-friday?campaign=Twitter_atn |author=Patra, Kevin |website=NFL.com |date=December 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Update on Rob Gronkowski |url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/12/01/update-rob-gronkowski |website=Patriots.com |date=December 1, 2016 |access-date=December 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203061207/http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/12/01/update-rob-gronkowski |archive-date=December 3, 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> He was officially placed on injured reserve on December 3, 2016, after having surgery the previous day.<ref>{{cite web |title=Patriots place TE Rob Gronkowski on Injured Reserve; Sign RB DJ Foster to the 53-man roster |url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/12/03/patriots-place-te-rob-gronkowski-injured-reserve-sign-rb-dj-foster-53-man-roster |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012035209/http://www.patriots.com/news/2016/12/03/patriots-place-te-rob-gronkowski-injured-reserve-sign-rb-dj-foster-53-man-roster |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 12, 2017 |website=Patriots.com |date=December 3, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots officially place Rob Gronkowski on IR |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000750132/article/patriots-officially-place-rob-gronkowski-on-ir?campaign=tw-nf-sf44743935-sf44743935 |website=NFL.com |author=Shook, Nick |date=December 3, 2016}}</ref> He finished the season with 25 receptions on 38 targets for 540 yards and three touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GronRo00/gamelog/2016/ |title=Rob Gronkowski 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> His 21.6 yards per reception ranked first among NFL tight ends in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.playerprofiler.com/nfl/rob-gronkowski |title=Rob Gronkowski Advanced Stats and Metrics Profile: Efficiency|work=PlayerProfiler.com}}</ref> Gronkowski was on injured reserve when the Patriots won [[Super Bowl LI]] on February 5, 2017. In the game, the Patriots defeated the [[2016 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] by a score of 34\u201328, earning Gronkowski his second Super Bowl championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201702050atl.htm|title=Super Bowl LI - New England Patriots vs. Atlanta Falcons - February 5th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2016.htm|title=2016 New England Patriots Statistics & Players|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 6, 2017}}</ref> Despite missing eight games, Gronkowski was still ranked 23rd by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000814687/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-23-Rob-Gronkowski|title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 23 Rob Gronkowski|website=NFL.com|accessdate=June 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\nGronkowski began the 2017 season healthy after missing much of the previous season on the [[injured reserve]] list. Gronkowski injured his groin during a Week 2 victory over the [[2017 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], leaving the game early, but the injury did not result in missing any further games. Before the injury, he had recorded six receptions for 116 yards and a 53-yard touchdown.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709170nor.htm|title=New England Patriots at New Orleans Saints - September 17th, 2017|work=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]]|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rob Gronkowski\u2019s groin injury is probably not serious, but the Patriots will test it anyway|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2017/9/17/16322958/rob-gronkowski-patriots-saints-possible-back-injury|website=sbnation|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref> By the end of Week 4, he was occupying his familiar role as the team leader in receptions and receiving yardage, but a thigh [[contusion]] suffered in practice prior to the ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' game against the [[2017 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in Week 5 caused him to miss that game entirely.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots\u2019 Rob Gronkowski Misses Thursday Night Football, Expected To Play In Week 7|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2017/10/05/patriots-rob-gronkowski-reportedly-out-vs-buccaneers/|accessdate=October 11, 2017}}</ref> In Week 6, Gronkowski caught six passes for 83 receiving yards and two receiving touchdowns as the Patriots defeated the [[2017 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] by a score of 24\u201317. His 33-yard catch put the Patriots in the lead as well as overcoming a 14-point deficit.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201710150nyj.htm |title=New England Patriots at New York Jets - October 15th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> In Week 12, against the [[2017 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], Gronkowski caught five passes for 82 receiving yards and two receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201711260nwe.htm |title=Miami Dolphins at New England Patriots - November 26th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> This was his 16th multiple touchdown game, which broke the franchise record previously held by [[Randy Moss]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2017/11/27/rob-gronkowski-sets-patriots-record-for-multiple-td-games/ |title=Rob Gronkowski sets Patriots record for multiple-TD games |date=November 27, 2017 |website=Boston Herald |language=en-US |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week 13 against the [[2017 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Gronkowski had nine receptions for 147 receiving yards as the Patriots won 23\u20133.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712030buf.htm |title=New England Patriots at Buffalo Bills - December 3rd, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> However, after Bills rookie cornerback [[Tre'Davious White]] intercepted a pass intended for Gronkowski during the fourth quarter, Gronkowski responded by jumping elbow-first onto White, drawing a personal foul penalty and giving White a concussion. Gronkowski was upset, claiming that White should have been flagged for a pass interference penalty.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bergman|first1=Jeremy|title=Rob Gronkowski: Refs are calling 'craziest stuff' on me|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000887147/article/rob-gronkowski-refs-are-calling-craziest-stuff-on-me|publisher=NFL|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> On December 4, the day after the game, Gronkowski was suspended for one game for his hit on White.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sessler|first1=Marc|title=Rob Gronkowski suspended one game for hit on Tre'Davious White|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000887903/article/rob-gronkowski-suspended-one-game-for-late-hit|publisher=NFL|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> The next day, December 5, the NFL denied Gronkowski's appeal of the one-game suspension.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2017/12/05/rob-gronkowski-suspension-appeal-patriots-nfl/|title=Rob Gronkowski's 1 Game Suspension Upheld By NFL|publisher=boston.cbslocal.com |accessdate=December 5, 2017}}</ref> With Gronkowski suspended for the Patriots' Week 14 game against the Miami Dolphins, the Patriots lost 20\u201327.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2017/12/11/16765254/new-england-patriots-miami-dolphins-recap-monday-night-football-upset|title=5 reasons the Dolphins were able to upset the Patriots on \u2018Monday Night Football\u2019|publisher=SBNation.com|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following week, in a 27\u201324 win on the road against the [[2017 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Gronkowski caught nine passes for a career-high 168 yards. Gronkowski caught three consecutive passes for 69 yards on the Patriots' game-winning drive, and then caught the ensuing two-point conversion to put the Patriots up by 3.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712170pit.htm |title=New England Patriots at Pittsburgh Steelers - December 17th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=April 14, 2018}}</ref> He eclipsed the 1,000-yard mark on the season for the fourth time in his career, joining [[Tony Gonzalez]] and [[Jason Witten]] as the only NFL tight ends with four 1,000-yard seasons.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Brady produces 53rd comeback win from fourth-quarter deficit|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/new-england-patriots/post/_/id/4809382/tom-brady-produces-53rd-comeback-win-from-fourth-quarter-deficit|author=Reiss, Mike|website=ESPN.com|date=December 18, 2017}}</ref> His performance in Week 15 earned him AFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rob Gronkowski, Gurley among Players of the Week|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895841/article/rob-gronkowski-gurley-among-players-of-the-week|author=Lam, Quang M.|website=NFL.com|date=December 20, 2017}}</ref> On December 19, 2017, Gronkowski was named to his fifth Pro Bowl.<ref>{{cite web|title=NFL announces 2018 Pro Bowl rosters|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895772/article/nfl-announces-2018-pro-bowl-rosters|website=NFL.com|date=December 19, 2017|accessdate=December 23, 2017}}</ref> He finished the 2017 season with 69 receptions for 1,084 yards, most among tight ends, and eight touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GronRo00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Rob Gronkowski 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017/receiving.htm |title=2017 NFL Receiving |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref> In January 2018, he was named to the Associated Press' All-Pro First Team,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/pats-gronkowski-tops-aps-list-top-nfl-tight-162404429--nfl.html|title=Pats' Gronkowski tops AP's list of top NFL tight ends|website=sports.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=February 24, 2019}}</ref> earning him a $2.5 million incentive that was added to his contract during the 2017 offseason.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2018/01/05/rob-gronkowski-nfl-all-pro-bonus-patriots-tom-brady/|title=Rob Gronkowski Earns Nice Bonus For Making 2017 All-Pro Team|date=January 5, 2018|access-date=January 5, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/patriots/2017/05/23/rob-gronkowski-agrees-new-deal-with-patriots/jGkWxHUC9omX3hmlK0aRAL/story.html|title=Rob Gronkowski agrees to restructured deal with Patriots - The Boston Globe|work=BostonGlobe.com|access-date=January 12, 2018}}</ref> The Patriots finished with a 13\u20133 record and earned a first round bye.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nwe/2017.htm |title=2017 New England Patriots Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2017.htm |title=2017 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 35, Tennessee Titans 14|Divisional Round]] against the [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], he finished with six receptions for receiving 81 yards and a receiving touchdown in the 35\u201314 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Tennessee Titans at New England Patriots - January 13th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref> On January 21, 2018, Gronkowski suffered a concussion on a 21-yard reception during the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 24, Jacksonville Jaguars 20|AFC Championship Game]] against the [[2017 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], being placed on concussion protocol, and did not return to the game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801210nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship - Jacksonville Jaguars at New England Patriots - January 21st, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gronkowski suffers head injury in Pats' AFC title win|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000908639/article/gronkowski-suffers-head-injury-in-pats-afc-title-win|website=NFL.com|accessdate=January 22, 2018|date=January 21, 2018}}</ref> He would be cleared from the protocol just in time for [[Super Bowl LII]] against the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]]. During the Super Bowl, he finished with 116 receiving yards and two touchdowns. In the closing seconds, he attempted to catch a [[Hail Mary pass]], but failed, and the Patriots lost 33\u201341.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201802040nwe.htm |title=Super Bowl LII - Philadelphia Eagles vs. New England Patriots - February 4th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Bergman|first1=Jeremy|title=Rob Gronkowski mulling football future after loss|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000914570/article/rob-gronkowski-mulling-football-future-after-loss|publisher=NFL|accessdate=February 4, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 15th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2018/0ap3000000937715/Top-100-Players-of-2018-Rob-Gronkowski-No-15 |title='Top 100 Players of 2018': New England Patriots tight end Rob Gronkowski |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"nfl.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/player/robgronkowski/497240/careerstats|title=Rob Gronkowski: Career Stats at NFL.com|website=www.nfl.com|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\n[[File:Rob Gronkowski after winning Super Bowl LIII, February 2019.png|thumb|Gronkowski after winning [[Super Bowl LIII]], February 3, 2019|250x250px]]\nDespite rumors of retirement on April 24, Gronkowski announced that he had met with head coach [[Bill Belichick]] and that he would return for the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.nbcsports.com/boston/patriots/rob-gronkowski-i-met-bill-belichick-tell-him-im-2018 |title=Rob Gronkowski: I met with Bill Belichick to tell him I'm in for 2018 | first=Phil | last=Perry | date=April 24, 2018 | website=NBC Sports Boston | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> He returned to practice on June 5 after skipping minicamp, confirming his return.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/patriots/the_blitz/2018/06/rob_gronkowski_returns_to_patriots_practice_says_it_was_good|title = Rob Gronkowski returns to Patriots practice, says it was 'good decision' to skip offseason program|first = Stephen|last = Hewitt|website = BostonHerald.com|date = June 5, 2018|accessdate = July 1, 2018|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180702035531/http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/patriots/the_blitz/2018/06/rob_gronkowski_returns_to_patriots_practice_says_it_was_good|archive-date = July 2, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In the opening game against the [[2018 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Gronkowski had seven receptions for 123 yards and one touchdown in a 27\u201320 victory. He also fumbled for the first time since 2012.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2018/09/09/brady-gronk-open-season-with-27-20-win-over-texans/37766355/ | title=Brady, Gronk open season with 27\u201320 win over Texans | date=September 9, 2018 | agency=Associated Press | website=USA Today | language=en | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> However, in his next six games, Gronkowski had some limited production, totaling 22 receptions for 325 yards with no touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GronRo00/gamelog/2018/#104-109-sum:stats |title=Rob Gronkowski 2018 Game Log (Games 2\u20137)|website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> He scored his second touchdown of the season in the Week 12 victory over the [[2018 New York Jets season|New York Jets]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://patriotswire.usatoday.com/2018/11/25/watch-rob-gronkowski-end-td-drought-with-monstrous-catch/ |title=Watch Rob Gronkowski end TD drought with monstrous catch |last=McKenna |first=Henry |date=November 25, 2018 |website=Patriots Wire |language=en |access-date=December 6, 2018}}</ref> In Week 14, against the [[2018 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], he had eight receptions for 107 receiving yards and a receiving touchdown in the [[Miracle in Miami|34\u201333 loss]]. In the loss, a last-second victory by the Dolphins, Gronkowski unsuccessfully was the last line of defense on the game-winning play.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25493377 | title=Dolphins shock Patriots thanks to miracle last-second lateral play | first=Cameron | last=Wolfe | date=December 10, 2018 | website=ESPN.com | language=en | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref> This stemmed from Gronkowski often taking the field as a [[Safety (gridiron football position)|hybrid safety]] to defend against Hail Mary passes.<ref name=\"nfl.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2018/12/9/18133424/rob-gronkowski-new-england-patriots-miami-dolphins-miracle-touchdown|title=Why the hell was Gronk on the field for the Miracle in Miami?|last=Stites|first=Adam|date=2018-12-09|website=SBNation.com|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref> In the 2018 season, he finished with 47 receptions for 682 receiving yards and three receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/G/GronRo00.htm |title=Rob Gronkowski 2018 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Patriots made the playoffs as the #2-seed in the AFC. In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 41, Los Angeles Chargers 28|Divisional Round]] against the [[2018 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]], he had a 25-yard reception in the 41\u201328 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201901130nwe.htm |title=Divisional Round - Los Angeles Chargers at New England Patriots - January 13th, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 8, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 37, Kansas City Chiefs 31 (OT)|AFC Championship]] against the [[2018 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], he had six receptions for 79 receiving yards in the 37\u201331 overtime victory. During [[Super Bowl LIII]] against the [[2018 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], Gronkowski finished with 87 receiving yards as the Patriots won 13\u20133.<ref>{{cite web | title=Patriots defeat Rams 13\u20133 in Super Bowl LIII | url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001016157/article/patriots-defeat-rams-133-in-super-bowl-liii | first=Chris | last=Wesseling | date=February 3, 2019 | publisher=NFL | accessdate=March 27, 2019}}</ref> In the process, he set the record for catches and yards for tight ends in the Super Bowl with 23 catches and 297 yards. Gronkowski's biggest moment came when, with the score tied at 3 in the fourth quarter, he had a 29-yard catch from [[Tom Brady]] which took the Patriots to the two-yard line and set up the game's only touchdown, with [[Sony Michel]] scoring on a two-yard rush to put the Patriots ahead.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/super-bowl/2019/02/04/rob-gronkowski-retirement-new-england-patriots-super-bowl-2019/2765404002/ | title=With retirement question looming, Rob Gronkowski delivers lasting memories in Patriots' Super Bowl win | first=Nate | last=Davis | date=February 4, 2019 | website=USA Today | language=en | access-date=March 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Retirement====\nOn March 24, 2019, after nine seasons, Gronkowski announced his retirement from the NFL, at 29 years old, via [[Instagram]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001024012/article/patriots-te-rob-gronkowski-announces-retirement |title=Patriots TE Rob Gronkowski announces retirement |first=Jeremy |last=Bergman |website=NFL.com |date=March 24, 2019 |accessdate=March 24, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BvaCbK6BCvd/|title=Rob Gronkowski on Instagram: \"It all started at 20 years old on stage at the NFL draft when my dream came true, and now here I am about to turn 30 in a few months with a\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-03-29}}</ref> He further elaborated on his decision five months later saying that the pain and injuries he had suffered throughout his career had taken a toll on his [[mental health]],<blockquote>\"I was not in a good place. Football was bringing me down, and I didn't like it. I was losing that joy in life... I could play right now if I wanted to play. I\u2019m feeling good. Physically, I could do it. Mentally-wise, desire-wise, it's not there... I am very satisfied with where I am in life right now. I truly believe going through those tough times, nine years, off the field, on the field, has brought me to this point. I believe I\u2019m on the right path in my life.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27475715 |title=Gronkowski: Football was bringing me down |last=Reiss |first=Mike |date=2019-08-27 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2019-08-27}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\n===Tampa Bay Buccaneers===\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"I always said when I have that feeling, and it feels right, I will be ready to take the field again. And I have that feeling. I\u2019m ready.\"\n<br>\u2013Gronkowski on coming out of retirement, April 2020<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2020/04/21/rob-gronkowski-i-have-that-feeling-and-it-feels-right/ |title=Rob Gronkowski: I have that feeling, and it feels right |last=Williams|first=Charean |date=April 21, 2020 |website=ProFootballTalk |access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n| align = right\n| width = 28%\n}}\nOn April 21, 2020, the Patriots agreed to trade Gronkowski to the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] along with a seventh-round pick in exchange for a compensatory fourth round pick in the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Patriots to trade Rob Gronkowski to Buccaneers |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001110390/article/patriots-to-trade-rob-gronkowski-to-buccaneers |publisher=NFL |accessdate=April 21, 2020}}</ref> The trade reunited him with Brady, who signed with the Buccaneers a month prior.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Belson|first=Ken|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/21/sports/football/rob-gronkowski-tom-brady-buccaneers-patriots.html|title=Rob Gronkowski to Reunite With Tom Brady in Tampa Bay|date=2020-04-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-22|last2=Pennington|first2=Bill|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==NFL statistics==\n====Regular season====\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n| [[List of Super Bowl champions|Won the Super Bowl]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|\n| Led the league\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Team\n! colspan=\"2\" | Games\n! colspan=\"5\" | Receiving\n! colspan=\"5\" | Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\" | Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Long !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Long !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n![[2010 NFL season|2